{"title_page": "Robert Dallek", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Robert Dallek\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{b-da|May 16, 1934}}\n| birth_place       = [[Brooklyn, New York]], USA\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = {{plainlist|*[[Oxford University]]\n*[[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n*[[University of Texas]]\n*[[Dartmouth College]]\n*[[Boston University]]\n*[[Stanford University]]}}\n| patrons           =\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] <br> [[Columbia University]]\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = [[Bancroft Prize]] (1980)\n| signature         = \n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = Geraldine Kronmal (m. 1965)\n| children          = \n}}\n'''Robert A. Dallek''' (born May 16, 1934)<ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/article-1G2-3417900053/dallek-robert-1934.html www.encyclopedia.org]</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[historian]] specializing in the [[presidents of the United States]], including [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], [[John F. Kennedy]], [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], and [[Richard Nixon]].  He retired as a history professor at [[Boston University]] in 2004 and previously taught at [[Columbia University]], the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA), and [[Oxford University]].    He won the [[Bancroft Prize]] for his 1979 book ''[[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and American Foreign Policy, 1932\u20131945'' as well as other awards for scholarship and teaching.\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in [[Brooklyn, New York]], Dallek is the  son of Rubin (a business-machine dealer) and Esther (Fisher) Dallek.\n\nDallek attended the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]], graduating with a B.A. in history in June 1955. He did graduate work at [[Columbia University]], earning an M.A. in February 1957, and a Ph.D. in June 1964.  While working on his Ph.D., he was a history instructor at Columbia.\n\nHe married Geraldine Kronmal (a policy health analyst) on August 22, 1965.\n\n==Academic career==\nIn 1964-1994 Dallek advanced from assistant to full professor of history at the Department of History at [[University of California at Los Angeles]] (UCLA). From 1966 to 1968 he was a graduate adviser. From 1972 to 1974 he served as vice chair of the department. From 1981 to 1985 he was a research associate at the [[New Center for Psychoanalysis | Southern California Psychoanalytic Institute]]. In 1993 he was a visiting professor at the [[California Institute of Technology]], and from 1994 to 1995 he was the [[Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Professor of American History]] at [[Oxford University]], which in 1995 awarded him an honorary M.A.\n\nSince 1996 Dallek has been a visiting professor at the [[LBJ School of Public Affairs]] at the [[University of Texas]], and a professor of history at [[Boston University]]. From 2004 to 2005 he was Montgomery Fellow and a visiting professor in the history and government departments at [[Dartmouth College]]. \n\nDallek is a member of the [[Society for Historians of American Foreign Relations]].\n\n==''An Unfinished Life: John F. Kennedy, 1917-1963''==\nIn 2003, Dallek published the [[New York Times Bestseller]] ''[[An Unfinished Life: John F. Kennedy, 1917-1963]]'', the first major biography of [[John F. Kennedy]] in almost 40 years. Based on archival resources and unprecedented access to his medical records, it revealed his secret struggle with major health problems as well as his love affairs, the backstage role of his father, his appointment of his brother [[Robert F. Kennedy]] to the office of [[United States Attorney General]], and speculations about what the President would have done about the [[Vietnam War]] if he had lived.\n\n==''Nixon and Kissinger: Partners in Power''==\nIn 2007 Dallek published ''Nixon and Kissinger: Partners in Power'', which claims that they were visionaries and cynics at the same time, in an attempt to explain the ups and down of their diplomatic careers. \"The careers of both Nixon and Kissinger reflect the extent to which great accomplishments and public wrongdoing can spring from inner lives.\" The book was a finalist for the 2008 [[Pulitzer Prize in History]].\n\n==Works==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Democrat and Diplomat: The Life of William E. Dodd'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 1968) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Democrat_and_Diplomat.html?id=JRlCAAAAIAAJ read online]\n* ''1898: McKinley's Decision \u2013 The United States Declares War on Spain'' (New York: [[Chelsea House Publishers]], 1969) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/004388548?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''The Roosevelt Diplomacy and World War II'' (New York: [[Holt, Rinehart and Winston]], 1970) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000186190 read online]\n* ''The Dynamics of World Power: Western Europe'' (with [[Robert N. Burr]] and [[Walter LaFeber]]) (New York: [[Chelsea House Publishers]], 1973) [https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Dynamics_of_World_Power_Western_Euro.html?id=KAV3AAAAMAAJ read online]\n* ''The Dynamics of World Power: A Documentary History of United States Foreign Policy, 1945-1973'' (ed. [[Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr.]], with  [[Robert N. Burr]], and [[Walter LaFeber]]) (New York: [[Chelsea House Publishers]], 1973)  [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000587794?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''Franklin D. Roosevelt and American Foreign Policy, 1932\u20131945'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 1979) ([[Bancroft Prize]]) [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.85890 read online]\n* ''The American Style of Foreign Policy: Cultural Politics and Foreign Affairs'' (New York: [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]], 1983) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000153724?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''Ronald Reagan: The Politics of Symbolism'' (Cambridge, MA: [[Harvard University Press]], 1984, {{ISBN|978-0-674-77941-9}}) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000241486?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''Lone Star Rising: Lyndon Johnson and his Times, 1908\u20131960'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 1991) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Lone_Star_Rising.html?id=t_LjEJdaAiYC read online] [https://archive.org/details/lonestarrisingly00dall read online]\n* ''Franklin D. Roosevelt as World Leader: An Inaugural Lecture Delivered before the University of Oxford on 16 May 1995'' (New York: [[Clarendon Press]], 1995)\n* ''Hail to the Chief: The Making and Unmaking of American Presidents'' (New York: [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion]], 1996) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/003096471?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''Flawed Giant: Lyndon Johnson and his Times, 1961\u20131973'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 1998) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Flawed_Giant_Lyndon_Johnson_and_His_Time.html?id=G_J3PEegwdYC read online]\n* ''[[An Unfinished Life: John F. Kennedy, 1917\u20131963]]'' (Boston: [[Little, Brown and Company]], 2003)\n* ''Lyndon B. Johnson: Portrait of a President'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 2004) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Lyndon_B_Johnson.html?id=JIGcq0RXspMC read online]\n* ''Lessons from the Lives and Times of Presidents'' (Richmond, Virginia: [[University of Richmond]], 2004) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Lessons_from_the_Lives_and_Times_of_Pres.html?id=eRfvGwAACAAJ read online]\n* ''Let Every Nation Know: John F. Kennedy in His Own Words'' (with Terry Golway) (Naperville, IL: [[Sourcebooks]], 2006) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Let_Every_Nation_Know.html?id=fi41KR1bTEYC read online]\n* ''Nixon and Kissinger: Partners in Power'' (New York: [[HarperCollins]], 2007) [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/books/review/Lawrence-t.html? Review in New York Times]\n* ''Harry S. Truman: The 33rd President, 1945-1953'' ([[Times Books]], 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8050-6938-9}})\n* ''The Lost Peace: Leadership in a Time of Horror and Hope, 1945\u20131953'' ([[HarperCollins]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-06-162866-5}}) [https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/capsule-review/2010-11-01/lost-peace-leadership-time-horror-and-hope-1945-1953 Review in Foreign Affairs]\n* ''Camelot's Court: Inside the Kennedy White House'' (New York: [[HarperCollins]], 2013) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/book-review-camelots-court-inside-the-kennedy-white-house-by-robert-dallek/2013/10/25/5e987814-0e93-11e3-85b6-d27422650fd5_story.html Review in Washington Post]\n* ''Franklin D. Roosevelt: A Political Life'' (New York: [[Viking Press|Viking]], 2017, {{ISBN|9780525427902}})\n\n===Journal articles===\n* 'Franklin Roosevelt as world leader', ''The American Historical Review'', '''76''' (1971): 1503\u20131513\n* 'National mood and American foreign policy: a suggestive essay', ''American Quarterly'', '''34''' (1982): 229\u2013261\n* 'Lyndon Johnson and Vietnam: the making of a tragedy', ''Diplomatic History'', '''20''' (1996): 147\n* 'Tales of the tapes', ''Reviews in American History'', '''26''' (1998): 333\u2013338\n* 'John F. Kennedy's Civil Rights Quandary.' American History 38.3 (2003): 36\n\n===Essays in edited volumes===\n* ''American perceptions of the Soviet Union'', in Abbott Gleason (ed.), ''Cold War-Cold Peace: Soviet American Relations, 1933\u20131983'' (Boston: Beacon Press, 1975)\n* 'Triumphant America in a shaken world', in Sanford J. Ungar (ed.), ''Estrangement: America and the World''(New York: Oxford University Press, 1985)\n* ''When Presidents Become Weak'', in Walter Isaacson (ed.), ''Profiles in Leadership: Historians on the Elusive Quality of Greatness'' (New York: [[W. W. Norton & Company]], 2011)\n\n==TV appearances==\nDallek appeared on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' in July 2007.  He has made numerous appearances on [[CNN]] and on public television and radio, including several on-camera comments included the History Channel's \"JFK:A Presidency Revealed\" and the American Experience biographies \"F.D.R.\" and \"LBJ.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080829001414/http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/history/dallek/ UCLA Profile]\n*{{C-SPAN|Robert Dallek}}\n**[http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/21448-1/Robert+Dallek.aspx ''Booknotes'' interview with Dallek on ''Lone Star Rising''], September 22, 1991\n**[http://www.c-span.org/video/?197600-1/qa-robert-dallek C-SPAN ''Q&A'' interview with Dallek on ''Nixon and Kissinger: Partners in Power''], April 29, 2007\n*[http://radioopensource.org/robert-dallek-on-three-last-questions-about-jfk/ Robert Dallek on Three Last Questions about JFK (audiocast)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dallek, Robert}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jewish American historians]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Professors of American History]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Robert Dallek\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{b-da|May 16, 1934}}\n| birth_place       = [[Brooklyn, New York]], USA\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = {{plainlist|*[[Oxford University]]\n*[[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n*[[University of Texas]]\n*[[Dartmouth College]]\n*[[Boston University]]\n*[[Stanford University]]}}\n| patrons           =\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] <br> [[Columbia University]]\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = [[Bancroft Prize]] (1980)\n| signature         = \n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = Geraldine Kronmal (m. 1965)\n| children          = \n}}\n'''Robert A. Dallek''' (born May 16, 1934)<ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/article-1G2-3417900053/dallek-robert-1934.html www.encyclopedia.org]</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[historian]] specializing in the [[presidents of the United States]], including [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], [[John F. Kennedy]], [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], and [[Richard Nixon]].  He retired as a history professor at [[Boston University]] in 2004 and previously taught at [[Columbia University]], the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA), and [[Oxford University]].    He won the [[Bancroft Prize]] for his 1979 book ''[[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and American Foreign Policy, 1932\u20131945'' as well as other awards for scholarship and teaching.\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in [[Brooklyn, New York]], Dallek is the  son of Rubin (a business-machine dealer) and Esther (Fisher) Dallek.\n\nDallek attended the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]], graduating with a B.A. in history in June 1955. He did graduate work at [[Columbia University]], earning an M.A. in February 1957, and a Ph.D. in June 1964.  While working on his Ph.D., he was a history instructor at Columbia.\n\nHe married Geraldine Kronmal (a policy health analyst) on August 22, 1965.\n\n==Academic career==\nIn 1964-1994 Dallek advanced from assistant to full professor of history at the Department of History at [[University of California at Los Angeles]] (UCLA). From 1966 to 1968 he was a graduate adviser. From 1972 to 1974 he served as vice chair of the department. From 1981 to 1985 he was a research associate at the [[New Center for Psychoanalysis | Southern California Psychoanalytic Institute]]. In 1993 he was a visiting professor at the [[California Institute of Technology]], and from 1994 to 1995 he was the [[Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Professor of American History]] at [[Oxford University]], which in 1995 awarded him an honorary M.A.\n\nSince 1996 Dallek has been a visiting professor at the [[LBJ School of Public Affairs]] at the [[University of Texas]], and a professor of history at [[Boston University]]. From 2004 to 2005 he was Montgomery Fellow and a visiting professor in the history and government departments at [[Dartmouth College]]. \n\nDallek is a member of the [[Society for Historians of American Foreign Relations]].\n\n==''An Unfinished Life: John F. Kennedy, 1917-1963''==\nIn 2003, Dallek published the [[New York Times Bestseller]] ''[[An Unfinished Life: John F. Kennedy, 1917-1963]]'', the first major biography of [[John F. Kennedy]] in almost 40 years. Based on archival resources and unprecedented access to his medical records, it revealed his secret struggle with major health problems as well as his love affairs, the backstage role of his father, his appointment of his brother [[Robert F. Kennedy]] to the office of [[United States Attorney General]], and speculations about what the President would have done about the [[Vietnam War]] if he had lived.\n\n==''Nixon and Kissinger: Partners in Power''==\nIn 2007 Dallek published ''Nixon and Kissinger: Partners in Power'', which claims that they were visionaries and cynics at the same time, in an attempt to explain the ups and down of their diplomatic careers. \"The careers of both Nixon and Kissinger reflect the extent to which great accomplishments and public wrongdoing can spring from inner lives.\" The book was a finalist for the 2008 [[Pulitzer Prize in History]].\n\n==Works==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Democrat and Diplomat: The Life of William E. Dodd'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 1968) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Democrat_and_Diplomat.html?id=JRlCAAAAIAAJ read online]\n* ''1898: McKinley's Decision \u2013 The United States Declares War on Spain'' (New York: [[Chelsea House Publishers]], 1969) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/004388548?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''The Roosevelt Diplomacy and World War II'' (New York: [[Holt, Rinehart and Winston]], 1970) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000186190 read online]\n* ''The Dynamics of World Power: Western Europe'' (with [[Robert N. Burr]] and [[Walter LaFeber]]) (New York: [[Chelsea House Publishers]], 1973) [https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Dynamics_of_World_Power_Western_Euro.html?id=KAV3AAAAMAAJ read online]\n* ''The Dynamics of World Power: A Documentary History of United States Foreign Policy, 1945-1973'' (ed. [[Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr.]], with  [[Robert N. Burr]], and [[Walter LaFeber]]) (New York: [[Chelsea House Publishers]], 1973)  [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000587794?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''Franklin D. Roosevelt and American Foreign Policy, 1932\u20131945'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 1979) ([[Bancroft Prize]]) [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.85890 read online]\n* ''The American Style of Foreign Policy: Cultural Politics and Foreign Affairs'' (New York: [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]], 1983) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000153724?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''Ronald Reagan: The Politics of Symbolism'' (Cambridge, MA: [[Harvard University Press]], 1984, {{ISBN|978-0-674-77941-9}}) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000241486?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''Lone Star Rising: Lyndon Johnson and his Times, 1908\u20131960'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 1991) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Lone_Star_Rising.html?id=t_LjEJdaAiYC read online] [https://archive.org/details/lonestarrisingly00dall read online]\n* ''Franklin D. Roosevelt as World Leader: An Inaugural Lecture Delivered before the University of Oxford on 16 May 1995'' (New York: [[Clarendon Press]], 1995)\n* ''Hail to the Chief: The Making and Unmaking of American Presidents'' (New York: [[Hyperion Books|Hyperion]], 1996) [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/003096471?type%5B%5D=author&lookfor%5B%5D=%22Dallek%2C%20Robert.%22 read online]\n* ''Flawed Giant: Lyndon Johnson and his Times, 1961\u20131973'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 1998) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Flawed_Giant_Lyndon_Johnson_and_His_Time.html?id=G_J3PEegwdYC read online]\n* ''[[An Unfinished Life: John F. Kennedy, 1917\u20131963]]'' (Boston: [[Little, Brown and Company]], 2003)\n* ''Lyndon B. Johnson: Portrait of a President'' (New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 2004) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Lyndon_B_Johnson.html?id=JIGcq0RXspMC read online]\n* ''Lessons from the Lives and Times of Presidents'' (Richmond, Virginia: [[University of Richmond]], 2004) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Lessons_from_the_Lives_and_Times_of_Pres.html?id=eRfvGwAACAAJ read online]\n* ''Let Every Nation Know: John F. Kennedy in His Own Words'' (with Terry Golway) (Naperville, IL: [[Sourcebooks]], 2006) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Let_Every_Nation_Know.html?id=fi41KR1bTEYC read online]\n* ''Nixon and Kissinger: Partners in Power'' (New York: [[HarperCollins]], 2007) [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/books/review/Lawrence-t.html? Review in New York Times]\n* ''Harry S. Truman: The 33rd President, 1945-1953'' ([[Times Books]], 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8050-6938-9}})\n* ''The Lost Peace: Leadership in a Time of Horror and Hope, 1945\u20131953'' ([[HarperCollins]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-06-162866-5}}) [https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/capsule-review/2010-11-01/lost-peace-leadership-time-horror-and-hope-1945-1953 Review in Foreign Affairs]\n* ''Camelot's Court: Inside the Kennedy White House'' (New York: [[HarperCollins]], 2013) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/book-review-camelots-court-inside-the-kennedy-white-house-by-robert-dallek/2013/10/25/5e987814-0e93-11e3-85b6-d27422650fd5_story.html Review in Washington Post]\n* ''Franklin D. Roosevelt: A Political Life'' (New York: [[Viking Press|Viking]], 2017, {{ISBN|9780525427902}})\n\n===Journal articles===\n* 'Franklin Roosevelt as world leader', ''The American Historical Review'', '''76''' (1971): 1503\u20131513\n* 'National mood and American foreign policy: a suggestive essay', ''American Quarterly'', '''34''' (1982): 229\u2013261\n* 'Lyndon Johnson and Vietnam: the making of a tragedy', ''Diplomatic History'', '''20''' (1996): 147\n* 'Tales of the tapes', ''Reviews in American History'', '''26''' (1998): 333\u2013338\n* 'John F. Kennedy's Civil Rights Quandary.' American History 38.3 (2003): 36\n\n===Essays in edited volumes===\n* ''American perceptions of the Soviet Union'', in Abbott Gleason (ed.), ''Cold War-Cold Peace: Soviet American Relations, 1933\u20131983'' (Boston: Beacon Press, 1975)\n* 'Triumphant America in a shaken world', in Sanford J. Ungar (ed.), ''Estrangement: America and the World''(New York: Oxford University Press, 1985)\n* ''When Presidents Become Weak'', in Walter Isaacson (ed.), ''Profiles in Leadership: Historians on the Elusive Quality of Greatness'' (New York: [[W. W. Norton & Company]], 2011)\n\n==TV appearances==\nDallek appeared on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' in July 2007.  He has made numerous appearances on [[CNN]] and on public television and radio, including several on-camera comments included the History Channel's \"JFK:A Presidency Revealed\" and the American Experience biographies \"F.D.R.\" and \"LBJ.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080829001414/http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/history/dallek/ UCLA Profile]\n*{{C-SPAN|Robert Dallek}}\n**[http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/21448-1/Robert+Dallek.aspx ''Booknotes'' interview with Dallek on ''Lone Star Rising''], September 22, 1991\n**[http://www.c-span.org/video/?197600-1/qa-robert-dallek C-SPAN ''Q&A'' interview with Dallek on ''Nixon and Kissinger: Partners in Power''], April 29, 2007\n*[http://radioopensource.org/robert-dallek-on-three-last-questions-about-jfk/ Robert Dallek on Three Last Questions about JFK (audiocast)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dallek, Robert}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jewish American historians]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Professors of American History]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBooks:Fixinglinks to disambiguation pages, replaced: [[Hyperion Books| \u