e European Community|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Origins_and_development_of_the_Europ.html?id=_he0AAAAIAAJ|publisher= Leicester: [[University of Leicester|Leicester University Press]]|isbn= 9780718514280}}\n* {{cite book |last1= Guieu|first1= Jean-Michel|last2= Le Dr\u00e9au|first2= Christophe|title= Le \" Congr\u00e8s de l'Europe \" \u00e0 La Haye (1948\u20132008)|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=0JM1BquiVHIC|location= Bruxelles, Bern, Berlin, Frankfurt am Main, New York, Oxford, Wien|series= Euroclio series|language= French|volume= 49|publisher= Peter Lang|date= 2009|isbn= 9789052015736 | ref= harv}}\n* {{citation|last= Burleigh|first= Michael|author-link1= Michael Burleigh|year= 2001|title= The Third Reich: A New History|publisher= [[Hill & Wang|Hill and Wang]]|oclc= 44084002}}\n* {{citation|last= Mazower|first= Mark|author-link1= Mark Mazower|year= 2013|title= Hitler's Empire: Nazi Rule in Occupied Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=opefF4rAL6YC|publisher= [[Penguin Books|Penguin UK]]|isbn=9780141917504}}\n* {{cite book|last= Schwarz|first= Dieter|year=1938|title= Die Freimaurerei: Weltanschauung, Organisation und Politik|url= https://archive.org/details/Schwarz-Dieter-Die-Freimaurerei|publisher=[[Franz Eher Nachfolger|Franz Eher Nachfolger GmbH]]|location=Berlin | ref= harv}} (with an introduction by [[Reinhard Heydrich]])\n* {{cite book|last= Denslow|first= William R.|year=1957|title= 10,000 Famous Freemasons|url= http://www.phoenixmasonry.org/10,000_famous_freemasons/Volume_1_A_to_D.htm|publisher=[[Robert Macoy|Macoy Publishing & Masonic Supply Co., Inc.]]|location=Richmond, Virginia | ref= harv}} (with an introduction by [[Harry S. Truman]])\n* {{citation|last= Jaje\u015bniak-Quast|first= Dagmara|year= 2010|title= Einzelver\u00f6ffentlichungen des Deutschen Historischen Instituts Warschau Bd. 23|chapter= Polish Economic Circles and the Question of the Common European Market after World War I|chapterurl=http://www.perspectivia.net/content/publikationen/ev-warschau/kohlrausch-steffen-wiederkehr_cultures/jajesniak-quast_circles|publisher= Fibre-Verlag|isbn= 9783938400586}}\n* {{cite book |last= Levy|first= Jonathan|title= The Intermarium: Wilson, Madison, and East Central European Federalismahren|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wNb4RXDxEt4C|publisher= [[Universal Publishers (United States)|Universal-Publishers]]|date= 2007|isbn= 9781581123692| ref= harv}} The role of Count Coudenhove-Kalergi in east central European federalism is reexamined.\n* {{citation|last= Churchill|first= Winston S.|year= 2003|title= Never Give In!: The Best of Winston Churchill's Speeches|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Never_Give_In.html?id=xPR69tBYyWkC|publisher= [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion]]|isbn= 9781401300562}}\n* {{citation|last= Langmuir|first= Gavin I.|authorlink= Gavin I. Langmuir|title= History, Religion, and Antisemitism|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/History_Religion_and_Antisemitism.html?id=F1ySMxcXkjIC|publisher= |isbn= 9780520912267|date= 8 May 1990}}\n* {{citation|last= Robertson|first= Ritchie|author-link1= Ritchie Robertson|year= 1999|title= The \"Jewish Question\" in German Literature, 1749\u20131939: Emancipation and Its Discontents|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=laFtAAAAMAAJ|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]|isbn= 9780198186311}}\n* {{citation|last1= Pempel|first1= T.J.|author-link1= T. J. Pempel|last2= Lee|first2= Chung-Min|year= 2012|title= Security Cooperation in Northeast Asia: Architecture and Beyond|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=umb2lVHU81IC|publisher= [[Routledge]]|isbn= 9781136309847}}\n* {{cite book |last= Zuber|first= Otto|year= 1995|title= Jahrbuch der Forschungsloge Quatuor Coronati|publisher= [[Research Lodge|Forschungsloge]] Quatuor Coronati|location= Bayreuth|volume= 32|chapter= RICHARD NIKOLAUS Graf COUDENHOVE-KALERGI als Freimaurer|language= German|chapterurl= https://archive.org/details/DolddownloadrichardNikolausGrafCoudenhove-kalergi1894-1972 | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |last= Pernhorst|first= Christian|year= 2008|title= Das paneurop\u00e4ische Verfassungsmodell des Grafen Richard N. Coudenhove-Kalergi|publisher= Nomos Verlag|url= https://books.google.com/books/about/Das_paneurop%C3%A4ische_Verfassungsmodell_de.html?id=3l4NNAAACAAJ|language= German|isbn= 9783832932022 | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |editor-last=Kosch|editor-first=Wilhelm|title=Deutsches Literatur-Lexikon. das 20. Jahrhundert <small>Band 5: Butensch\u00f6n \u2013 Dedo</small>|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NmR_GZTZOecC|language=German| location = |publisher=Walter de Gruyter|date= 2003|isbn=9783110961119 | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Duchhardt |first=Heinz |date=2005 |title=Option Europa: deutsche, polnische und ungarische Europapl\u00e4ne des 19. und 20. Jahrhunderts Band 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BPjFiEV1PDQC |language=German |location= |publisher=[[Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht]] |isbn=9783525362877 | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Coudenhove-Kalergi |first=Richard Nikolaus |date=1925 |title=Praktischer Idealismus |trans-title=Practical Idealism |url=https://archive.org/details/PraktischerIdealismus1925 |language=German |location=Wien-Leipzig |publisher=Pan-Europa-Verlag |id=UBR069031840355 |isbn= |accessdate=7 November 2014 | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |last= Coudenhove-Kalergi|first= Richard Nikolaus|year= 1953 |title= An Idea Conquers the World| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-VY1AQAAIAAJ|publisher= [[Hutchinson (publisher)|Hutchinson]] |location= London | ref= harv}} (New York: Roy Publishers)\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons and category-inline|Count Richard Nikolaus von Coudenhove-Kalergi|Count Richard Nikolaus von Coudenhove-Kalergi}}\n* [http://www.paneuropa.org/ International Paneuropean Union]\n* [http://www.european-society-coudenhove-kalergi.org/start_home1.asp European Society Coudenhove-Kalergi]\n* Archival sources on the [http://archives.eui.eu/en/fonds/181668?item=PAN/EU Paneuropean Union] and the [http://archives.eui.eu/en/fonds/158657?item=ME.05.03 European Parliamentary Union] at the [http://www.eui.eu/Research/HistoricalArchivesOfEU/Index.aspx Historical Archives of the EU] in Florence\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/003509}}\n* [https://www.mediathek.at/nc/type/8000/searchQuery/867/hash/fKm5j3o8/ Recordings of interviews and speeches with Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi] in the Online Archive of the [[\u00d6sterreichische Mediathek]] (in German). Retrieved 29 July 2019\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Coudenhove-Kalergi|House of Coudenhove-Kalergi]]|16 November|1894|27 July|1972|name=Richard Nikolaus Eijiro Graf von Coudenhove-Kalergi}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl|title=International President of the [[Paneuropean Union]]|years=1926\u20131972}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Otto von Habsburg]] <small>(elected in 1973)</small>}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Charlemagne Prize recipients}}\n{{Sonning Prize laureates}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coudenhove-Kalergi, Count Richard Nikolaus Von}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:Austrian politicians]]\n[[Category:Austrian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Austrian politicians of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:European integration pioneers]]\n[[Category:Coudenhove-Kalergi|Richard]]\n[[Category:Kallergis family|Richard]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Sacred Treasure, 1st class]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Counts of Austria]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:University of Vienna alumni]]\n[[Category:New York University faculty]]\n[[Category:European Union diplomats]]\n[[Category:Pan-European nationalism]]\n[[Category:History of the European Union]]\n[[Category:People from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Deaths in Austria]]\n[[Category:Burials in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Austrian Freemasons]]\n[[Category:Austrian officials of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Austrian anti-communists]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox noble\n|name        = Richard von Coudenhove-Kalergi\n|title       = Count of Coudenhove-Kalergi\n|image       = File:Graf Richard Nikolaus von Coudenhove-Kalergi (1894\u20131972) ~1930.jpg\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1894|11|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1972|7|27|1894|11|16|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Schruns, Austria]]\n|father      = [[Heinrich von Coudenhove-Kalergi]]\n|mother      = [[Mitsuko Aoyama]]\n|noble family= [[Coudenhove-Kalergi]]\n|occupation  = [[Politician]]\n}}\n\n'''Richard Nikolaus Eijiro, Count of Coudenhove-Kalergi'''<ref>\n* German: ''Richard Nikolaus Eijiro Graf von Coudenhove-Kalergi'' ({{German title Graf}}).\n* Japanese: {{nihongo|\u30ea\u30d2\u30e3\u30eb\u30c8\u30fb\u30cb\u30b3\u30e9\u30a6\u30b9\u30fb\u6804\u6b21\u90ce\u30fb\u30af\u30fc\u30c7\u30f3\u30db\u30fc\u30d5\uff1d\u30ab\u30ec\u30eb\u30ae\u30fc\u4f2f\u7235||Rihyaruto Nikorausu Eijir\u014d K\u016bdenh\u014dfu-Karerug\u012b Hakushaku}}.</ref> (16 November 1894 \u2013 27 July 1972) was an Austrian-Japanese politician, philosopher and [[Count]] of [[Coudenhove-Kalergi]]. A pioneer of [[European integration]], he served as the founding president of the [[Paneuropean Union]] for 49 years. His parents were [[Heinrich von Coudenhove-Kalergi]], an Austro-Hungarian diplomat and [[Mitsuko Aoyama]], the daughter of an oil merchant, antiques-dealer and major landowner in [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{harvnb|Tozawa|2013a}}, [http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/mitsuko2-1.htm chpt. (1)]</ref> His childhood name in Japan was '''Aoyama Eijiro'''. He became a [[Czechoslovak]] citizen in 1919 and then took French nationality from 1939 until his death.\n\nHis first book, ''[[Pan-Europa]]'', was published in 1923 and contained a membership form for the Pan-Europa movement, which held its first Congress in 1926 in [[Vienna]]. In 1927, [[Aristide Briand]] was elected honorary president of the Pan-Europa movement. Public figures who attended Pan-Europa congresses included [[Albert Einstein]], [[Thomas Mann]] and [[Sigmund Freud]].<ref>{{cite web |last= Oca\u00f1a |first= Juan Carlos |url= http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/SPRINGcoudenhove.htm |title= Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi |publisher= [[Spartacus Educational]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121024075148/http://www.spartacus.schoolnet.co.uk/SPRINGcoudenhove.htm |archivedate= 24 October 2012 |accessdate= 17 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi was the first recipient of the [[Charlemagne Prize]] in 1950. The 1972\u20131973 academic year at the [[College of Europe]] was named in his honour. Coudenhove-Kalergi proposed [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s \"[[Ode to Joy]]\" as the music for the [[European Anthem]]. He also proposed a [[Europe Day]], European postage stamp<ref name=\"Paneurope Suisse\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.suissemagazine.com/sites/paneurope/paneurope2009/rck.html|title= Richard N. de Coudenhove-Kalergi|publisher= Paneurope Suisse on Suisse magazine|language= French|accessdate= 31 October 2014|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140307192610/http://www.suissemagazine.com/sites/paneurope/paneurope2009/rck.html|archivedate= 7 March 2014}}</ref> and many artifacts for the movement (e.g. badges and pennants).<ref>{{harvnb|Persson|Str\u00e5th|2007}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=P32dNnKCYLcC&pg=PA99 p. 99]</ref>\n\n== Family roots ==\n[[File:E\u016dropo-placo C-K.JPG|thumb|Europa-Platz \u2013 Coudenhove-Kalergi in [[Klosterneuburg]], Austria]]\nCoudenhove-Kalergi was the second son of [[Heinrich von Coudenhove-Kalergi]] (1859\u20131906), an [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian]] count and diplomat of mixed European origin and [[Mitsuko Aoyama]] (1874\u20131941). His father, who spoke sixteen languages and embraced travel as the only means of prolonging life, yet died in his forties, had prematurely abandoned a career in the Austrian diplomatic service that took him to [[Athens]], [[Constantinople]], [[Rio de Janeiro]] and Tokyo, to devote himself to study and writing.\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi's parents met when his mother helped the Austro-Hungarian diplomat after he fell off a horse while riding in [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]. In commenting on their union, [[Whittaker Chambers]] described the future originator of Pan-Europe as \"practically a Pan-European organization himself.\" He elaborated: \"The [[Coudenhove]]s were a wealthy [[Flemish people|Flemish]] family that fled to Austria during the [[French Revolution]]. The [[Kallergis family|Kalergis]] were a wealthy Greek family from [[Crete]]. The line has been further crossed with Poles, Norwegians, [[Balts]], French and Germans, but since the families were selective as well as cosmopolitan, the hybridization has been consistently successful.\"<ref name=Whittaker>{{harvnb|Chambers|1944}}</ref> The [[Kallergis family|Kalergis family]] roots trace to [[Byzantium|Byzantine]] royalty via [[Venice|Venetian]] aristocracy, connecting with the [[Phokas (Byzantine family)|Phokas]] imperial dynasty. In 1300, Coudenhove-Kalergi's ancestor Alexios Phokas-Kalergis signed the treaty that made Crete a dominion of [[Republic of Venice|Venice]].\n\nDuring his childhood, Coudenhove-Kalergi's mother had read aloud to him ''[[Momotar\u014d]]'' and other Japanese fairy tales.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sucra.saitama-u.ac.jp/modules/xoonips/download.php/KYO-KJ00004106292.pdf?file_id=20505|title= \u7814\u7a76\u30ce\u30fc\u30c8 : \u6b27\u5dde\u7d71\u5408\u306e\u63d0\u5531\u8005\u3001\u30af\u30fc\u30c7\u30f3\u30db\u30fc\u30d5\u30fb\u30ab\u30ec\u30eb\u30ae\u30fc\u306e\u601d\u60f3\u3068\u884c\u52d5 An Advocate of the European Integration, Coudenhove-Kalergi's Original Idea and Activities|last1=NAITO|first1=Tetsuo|date= 31 March 2006|language=Japanese|publisher= [[Saitama University|Saitama United Cyber Repository of Academic Resources]] (SUCRA)|page=169|format= PDF|accessdate=22 October 2013|quote={{Lang|ja|\u5e7c\u304d\u65e5\u306b\u6bcd\u89aa\u306b\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u7ae5\u8a71\u3001\u4f8b\u3048\u3070\u300c\u6843\u592a\u90ce\u300d\u3092\u8aad\u3093\u3067\u3082\u3089\u3063\u305f\u3068\u306e\u5f7c\u306e\u56de\u60f3\u304c\u3042\u308b}}}}</ref>\n\n== Youth and education ==\n[[File:Pob\u011b\u017eovice z\u00e1mek(3).jpg|thumb|left|200px|The Ronsperg castle, his childhood home. Damaged during the Second World War, the repairs were overseen by a German from Japan [[Masumi Schmidt-Muraki]].]]\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi spent his adolescence on [[Bohemian]] family estates in [[Ronsperg]], known today as [[Pob\u011b\u017eovice]]. His father personally taught his two sons Russian and Hungarian and toughened them both physically and morally. He took them on long walks in all weather, made them sleep on straw mattresses and take cold showers, and taught them to shoot and fence so well that no one would ever dare challenge them. He also took them to [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] every Sunday. On every [[Good Friday]], as the [[Roman Rite|liturgy]] came to the exhortation \"oremus et pro perfidis Judaeis\" (\"[[Good Friday Prayer for the Jews|Let us also pray for the faithless Jews]]\"), the old count allegedly rose and walked out of the church in a protest against this supposed expression of [[antisemitism]].<ref name=Whittaker/>\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi studied at the [[Augustiner-Gymnasium Brixen|Augustiner-Gymnasium]] in [[Brixen]] before attending the [[Theresianische Akademie]] in Vienna from 1908 until 1913. He obtained his doctorate in philosophy with a thesis on ''Die Objectivit\u00e4t als Grundprinzip der Moral'' (Objectivity as the Fundamental Principle of Morals) in 1917 from the [[University of Vienna]].\n\nDuring his student years, Coudenhove-Kalergi married the famous Jewish Viennese actress [[Ida Roland]] in April 1915. His marriage to a [[divorcee|divorc\u00e9e]] thirteen years his senior, and a [[commoner]], caused a temporary split with his family. His mother Mitsuko did not accept Ida, considering her a \"[[Begging|beggar]] living on the [[Bank (geography)|riverbank]],\"<ref>{{harvnb|Tozawa|2013a}}, [http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/mitsuko2-3.htm chpt. (3)]: \"{{Lang|ja|\u6cb3\u539f\u4e5e\u98df}}\"</ref> a traditional Japanese point of view against actors and performers. His mother, as head of the family, banned him from the family temporarily, but retracted when Coudenhove-Kalergi became renowned for his pan-European concept.\n\n== Personal philosophy ==\nAristocratic in his origins and elitist in his ideas, Coudenhove-Kalergi identified and collaborated with such politicians as [[Engelbert Dollfuss]], [[Kurt Schuschnigg]], [[Otto von Habsburg]], [[Winston Churchill]], and [[Charles de Gaulle]].<ref>{{harvnb|Gehler||p=186}}</ref> His ideal political constituent was a [[gentleman]] who must respect and protect ladies, a person adhering to honesty, fair play, [[etiquette|courtesy]], and [[dialectics|rational discourse]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://wais.stanford.edu/ztopics/week110104/democracy_coudenhovekalergi_110104.htm|title= Democracy and the concept of gentleman: Coudenhove-Kalergi|last1=Hilton|first1=Ronald|authorlink1=Ronald Hilton|date= 19 November 2004|publisher= [[World Association of International Studies]] (WAIS) at [[Stanford University]]|accessdate=31 October 2014|quote=for Coudenhove-Kalergi it meant adherence to the ideals [ . . . ]: honesty, fair play, courtesy, rational discourse.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/english.html|title= \"Yuai\" for Understanding|publisher= [[Ichir\u014d Hatoyama|Yuai Association]]|accessdate= 4 February 2016|quote= ... the word Gentleman as he used referred to British type Gentleman in the chivalric medieval Europe, who may be characterized by such attributes as elegant, well-educated, polite, honest, humorous, cleanly, etc. ... Gentleman, however, must bear the moral responsibility to respect and protect Lady ...|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826122803/http://yuaikyoukai.com/english.html|archivedate= 26 August 2014}}</ref> He strove to replace the nationalist German ideal of [[Race (classification of human beings)|racial]] community with the goal of an ethnically heterogeneous European nation based on a commonality of culture{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}, a nation whose geniuses were the \"great Europeans\" such as [[abb\u00e9 de Saint-Pierre]], [[Immanuel Kant|Kant]], [[Napoleon]], [[Giuseppe Mazzini]], [[Victor Hugo]], and [[Friedrich Nietzsche]].\n\n== Pan-European political activist ==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-P0214-511, Berlin, Thomas Mann.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Ida Roland-Coudenhove-Kalergi and Thomas Mann in the second Pan-European Congress in [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin]] on 17 May 1930]]\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi is recognized as the founder of the first popular movement for a united Europe. His intellectual influences ranged from [[Immanuel Kant]], [[Rudolf Kjell\u00e9n]] and [[Oswald Spengler]] to [[Arthur Schopenhauer]] and [[Friedrich Nietzsche]]. In politics, he was an enthusiastic supporter of \"[[fourteen points]]\" made by [[Woodrow Wilson]] on 8 January 1918 and [[pacifism|pacifist]] initiatives of [[Kurt Hiller]]. In December 1921, he joined the [[Freemasonry|Masonic lodge]] \"Humanitas\" in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{harvnb|Jaje\u015bniak-Quast|2010|p=131}}</ref> In 1922, he co-founded{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} the Pan-European Union (PEU) with Archduke [[Otto von Habsburg]], as \"the only way of guarding against an eventual world hegemony by Russia.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Dorril|2000|p=165}}</ref> In 1923, he published a manifesto entitled ''Pan-Europa'', each copy containing a membership form which invited the reader to become a member of the [[International Paneuropean Union|Pan-Europa movement]]. He favored social democracy as an improvement on \"the feudal aristocracy of the sword\" but his ambition was to create a conservative society that superseded democracy with \"the social aristocracy of the spirit.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Rosamond|2000|pp=21\u201322}}</ref> European freemason lodges supported his movement, including the lodge Humanitas.<ref>{{harvnb|Ziegerhofer|2004}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=EHXg3QdGAtAC&pg=PA50 chpt. \u2164 \u2013 3]</ref> ''Pan-Europa'' was translated into the languages of European countries (excluding Italian, which edition was not published at that time) and a multitude of other languages, except for Russian.<ref name=\"Hewitson and D'Auria\">{{harvnb|Hewitson|D'Auria|2012}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7GRYc9sOoWUC&pg=PA107 p. 107]</ref>\n\nAccording to his autobiography, at the beginning of 1924 his friend [[Baron Louis de Rothschild]] introduced him to [[Max Warburg]] who offered to finance his movement for the next three years by giving him 60,000 gold marks. Warburg remained sincerely interested in the movement for the remainder of his life and served as an intermediate for Coudenhove-Kalergi with influential Americans such as banker [[Paul Warburg]] and financier [[Bernard Baruch]]. In April 1924, Coudenhove-Kalergi founded the journal ''Paneuropa'' (1924\u20131938) of which he was editor and principal author. The next year he started publishing his main work, the ''Kampf um Paneuropa '' (The fight for Paneuropa, 1925\u20131928, three volumes). In 1926, the first Congress of the Pan-European Union was held in Vienna and the 2,000 delegates elected Coudenhove-Kalergi as president of the Central Council, a position he held until his death in 1972.\n\nHis original vision was for a world divided into only five states: a United States of Europe that would link continental countries with French and Italian possessions in Africa; a Pan-American Union encompassing North and South Americas; the British Commonwealth circling the globe; the USSR spanning Eurasia; and a Pan-Asian Union whereby Japan and China would control most of the Pacific. To him, the only hope for a Europe devastated by war was to federate along lines that the Hungarian-born Romanian [[Aurel Popovici]] and others had proposed for the dissolved multinational Empire of Austria-Hungary. According to Coudenhove-Kalergi, Pan-Europe would encompass and extend a more flexible and more competitive Austria-Hungary, with English serving as the world language, spoken by everyone in addition to their native tongue. He believed that individualism and socialism would learn to cooperate instead of compete, and urged that capitalism and communism cross-fertilise each other just as the Protestant Reformation had spurred the Catholic Church to regenerate itself.<ref>{{harvnb|Lipgens|1984|p=712}}; {{harvnb|Johnston|1983|pp=320\u2013321}}</ref>\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi attempted to enlist prominent European politicians in his pan-European cause. He offered the presidency of the Austrian branch of the Pan-European Union to [[Ignaz Seipel]], who accepted the offer unhesitatingly and rewarded his beneficiary with an office in the old Imperial palace in Vienna. Coudenhove-Kalergi had less success with [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk|Tom\u00e1\u0161 Masaryk]], who referred him to his uncooperative Prime Minister [[Edvard Bene\u0161]]. However, the idea of pan-Europe elicited support from politicians as diverse as the Italian anti-Fascist politician [[Carlo Sforza]] and the German President of the [[Reichsbank]] under [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]], [[Hjalmar Schacht]]. Although Coudenhove-Kalergi found himself unable to sway [[Benito Mussolini]], his ideas influenced [[Aristide Briand]] through his inspired speech in favour of a European Union in the [[League of Nations]] on 8 September 1929, as well as his famous 1930 \"Memorandum on the Organisation of a Regime of European Federal Union.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Weigall|Stirk|1992|pp=11\u201315}}</ref>\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi proposed Beethoven's \"Ode to Joy\" as the [[Anthem of Europe]] in 1929,<ref name=\"Paneurope Suisse\" /> which he later proposed in 1955 as Anthem for the [[European Union]]. In 1930, he proposed a Europe Day in May<ref name=\"Paneurope Suisse\" /> and in 1932 he proposed to celebrate every 17 May, the anniversary of Aristide Briand's \"Memorandum\" being published in 1930.<ref name=\"Guieu and Le Dr\u00e9au\">{{harvnb|Guieu|Le Dr\u00e9au|2009}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=0JM1BquiVHIC&pg=PA176 p. 176]: \"{{Lang|fr| il a propos\u00e9 d\u00e8s 1932 une journ\u00e9e de l'Europe qui serait c\u00e9l\u00e9br\u00e9e chaque 17 mai, jour de la publication du M\u00e9morandum Briand.}}\"</ref> However, his Pan-Europeanism earned vivid loathing from [[Adolf Hitler]], who excoriated its pacifism and mechanical economism and belittled its founder as \"a bastard.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Burleigh|2001|p=426}}; {{harvnb|Lipgens|1984|p=37}}; Coudenhove-Kalergi once again approached Mussolini on 10 May 1933 in a futile attempt to form a union of Latin nations against the Third Reich. {{harv|Lipgens|1984|pp=180\u2013184}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Persson|Str\u00e5th|2007}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=P32dNnKCYLcC&pg=PA114 p. 114]</ref> Hitler's view of Coudenhove-Kalergi was that the \"rootless, cosmopolitan, and elitist half-breed\" was going to repeat the historical mistakes of Coudenhove ancestors who had served the [[House of Habsburg]].<ref>{{harvnb|Mazower|2013}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=opefF4rAL6YC&pg=PR691 p. 691]</ref> In 1928, Hitler wrote about his political opponent in his ''[[Zweites Buch]]'', describing him as \"{{Lang|de|[[wiktionary:aller-|Aller]] [[wiktionary:Welt|welts]] [[wiktionary:Bastard|bastarden]] (commonplace bastard) Coudenhove}}\".<ref>{{cite book |last= Hitler|first= Adolf|title= Zweites Buch|url= https://archive.org/details/HitlerAdolf-DasGeheimeZweiteBuch|language= German|publisher= |date= 1928|quote= {{Lang|de|Dieses Paneuropa nach Auffassung des Allerweltsbastarden Coudenhove w\u00fcrde der amerikanischen Union oder einem national erwachten China gegen\u00fcber einst dieselbe Rolle spielen wie der alt\u00f6sterreichische Staat gegen\u00fcber Deutschland oder Ru\u00dfland.}}}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Ziegerhofer|2004}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=EHXg3QdGAtAC&pg=PA425 p. 425]</ref>\n\nHitler did not share the ideas of his Austrian compatriot. He argued in his 1928 ''[[Hitler's Secret Book|Secret Book]]'' that they are unfit for the future defense of Europe against America. As America fills its North American [[lebensraum]], \u201cthe natural activist urge that is peculiar to young nations will turn outward.\u201d But then \u201ca pacifist-democratic Pan-European hodgepodge state\u201d would not be able to oppose the United States, as it is \u201caccording to the conception of that commonplace bastard, Coudenhove-Kalergi\u2026\u201d<ref>''[[Hitler's Secret Book]]'', 1928, (tr. Attanasio, Salvator, New York: Grove Press, 1962), p 107.</ref> Nazi criticism and propaganda against Coudenhove-Kalergi, and his European worldview, would decades later form the basis of the racist [[Kalergi plan]] conspiracy theory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilpost.it/2018/01/16/piano-kalergi/|title=Che cos\u2019\u00e8 \u2013 o sarebbe \u2013 il \"Piano Kalergi\" |language=italian|trans-title=What is - or would be - the \"Kalergi Plan\"|publisher=[[Il Post]]|date=January 16, 2018|quote=The reasons why Kalergi has once again become a scarecrow of the extreme right are quite evident by re-reading what Hitler wrote about him more than 80 years ago. Kalergi argued for the need to temper the differences between peoples in the name of a collective community, wider than the individual state, a recipe that can only be greeted with annoyance by the nationalists of the 1930s as well as those of the 2000s.}}</ref>\n\nNazis considered the Pan-European Union to be under the control of [[Freemasonry]].<ref>{{harvnb|Levy|2007}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=wNb4RXDxEt4C&pg=PA394 p. 394]</ref> In 1938, a [[Nazi propaganda]] book {{Lang|de|Die Freimaurerei: Weltanschauung, Organisation und Politik}} was released in German.<ref>The book had English edition as ''Freemasonry: Its World View, Organization and Policies''. (English full text: http://der-stuermer.org/freemasonryen.htm)</ref> It revealed Coudenhove-Kalergi's membership of Freemasonry, the organization [[Suppression of Freemasonry#Nazi Germany and occupied Europe|suppressed by Nazis]].<ref>{{harvnb|Schwarz|1938|p=22}}: \"{{Lang|de|der freimaurer Coudenhove-Kalergi}}\"</ref> On the other hand, his name was not to be found in Masonic directories ''10,000 Famous Freemasons'' published in 1957\u20131960 by the United States' freemasons.<ref>{{harvnb|Denslow|1957}}\u20131960</ref> He had already left the Viennese Masonic Lodge in 1926 to avoid the criticism that had occurred at that time against the relationship between the Pan-European movement and Freemasonry. He wrote about his Masonic membership in ''Ein Leben f\u00fcr Europa'' (A Life for Europe) published in 1966.<ref>{{harvnb|Jaje\u015bniak-Quast|2010|pp=131\u2013132}}; {{harvnb|Ziegerhofer|2004}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=EHXg3QdGAtAC&pg=PA57 p. 57]</ref> In fact, its Nazi propaganda book also described his action in 1924\u20131925 only. However, this propaganda also stated that \"The Grand Lodge of Wien went enthusiastically to work for the Pan European Union in a call to all Masonic chief authorities. Even the Masonic newspaper The Beacon enthused about the thoughts of the higher degree Freemason Coudenhove-Kalergi, and stated in March 1925:\n\"Freemasonry, especially Austrian Freemasonry, may be eminently satisfied to have Coudenhove-Kalergi among its members. Austrian Freemasonry can rightly report that Brother Coudenhove-Kalergi fights for his Pan European beliefs: political honesty, social insight, the struggle against lies, striving for the recognition and cooperation of all those of good will. In this higher sense, Brother Coudenhove-Kalergi's program is a Masonic work of the highest order, and to be able to work on it together is a lofty task for all brother Masons.\"\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090826133215/http://thecensureofdemocracy.150m.com/masonry.htm Web.archive.org]</ref>\n[[File:Casablanca, Paul Henreid.JPG|thumb|left|200px|Paul Henreid as Victor Laszlo in the cinematic trailer of ''Casablanca'']]\nAfter [[Anschluss|the annexation of Austria]] by the [[Third Reich]] in 1938, Coudenhove-Kalergi fled to [[Czechoslovakia]], and thence to France. As France fell to Germany in 1940, he escaped to the United States by way of Switzerland and Portugal. When he passed a few days after the successful escape to the United States, he listened to the radio announcing the possibility that he had died.<ref>{{harvnb|Coudenhove-Kalergi|1953|p=234}} (Roy Publishers)</ref> During [[World War II]], he continued his call for the unification of Europe along the Paris-London axis. His wartime politics and adventures served as the real life basis for fictional Resistance hero Victor Laszlo, the [[Paul Henreid]] character in ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]''. He published his work ''Crusade for Paneurope'' in 1944. His appeal for the unification of Europe enjoyed some support from [[Winston Churchill]], [[Allen Dulles]], and [[William Joseph Donovan|\"Wild Bill\" Donovan]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dorril|2000|pp=166\u2013167}}</ref> After the announcement of the [[Atlantic Charter]] on 14 August 1941, he composed a memorandum entitled \"Austria's Independence in the light of the Atlantic Charter\" and sent it to [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt]]. In his position statement, Coudenhove-Kalergi took up the goals of the charter and recommended himself as head of government in exile. Both Churchill and Roosevelt distanced themselves from this document. From 1942 until his return to France in 1945, he taught at the [[New York University]], which appointed him professor of history in 1944. At the same university Professor [[Ludwig von Mises]] studied currency problems for Coudenhove-Kalergi's movement.<ref>{{harvnb|Coudenhove-Kalergi|1953|p=247}} (Hutchinson)</ref>\n\nOn 22 July 1943, Nazis deprived him of his Doctor of Philosophy degree from the University of Vienna, with the [[racist]] argument, that as a \"Jew\" was not considered dignified an academic degree of a German university (\"''eines akademischen Grades einer deutschen Hochschule unw\u00fcrdig''\") \u2013 even though he was not Jewish nor was his family Jewish.<ref name=\"univie.ac.at\">{{cite web |url=http://gedenkbuch.univie.ac.at/index.php?id=435&no_cache=1&L=2&no_cache=1&person_single_id=40097&person_name=&person_geburtstag_tag=not_selected&person_geburtstag_monat=not_selected&person_geburtstag_jahr=not_selected&person_fakultaet=not_selected&person_kategorie=&person_volltextsuche=&search_person_x=1&result_page=19 |title=Richard Nikolaus Coudenhove-Kalergi |date=2014 |publisher=University of Vienna|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> His doctorate degree was only regranted on 15 May 1955 \u2013 a very long time after the end of [[Nazism]].<ref name=\"univie.ac.at\" />\n\nThe end of the [[World War II]] inaugurated a revival of pan-European hopes. In the winter of 1945, [[Harry S. Truman]] read an article in the December issue of ''[[Collier's|Collier's magazine]]'' that Coudenhove-Kalergi posted about the integration of Europe. His article impressed Truman, and it was adopted to the United States' official policy.<ref>{{harvnb|Tozawa|2013b}}, [http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/RCKexp2-3.htm chpt. (3)]</ref> Winston Churchill's celebrated speech of 19 September 1946 to the Academic Youth in [[Zurich]] commended \"the exertions of the Pan-European Union which owes so much to Count Coudenhove-Kalergi and which commanded the services of the famous French patriot and statesman Aristide Briand.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Lipgens|Loth|1988}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eJa0QAQiKNsC&pg=PA664 p. 664]; {{harvnb|Churchill|2003|pp=427\u2013430}}</ref> In November 1946 and the spring of 1947, Coudenhove-Kalergi circulated an enquiry addressed to members of European parliaments. This enquiry resulted in the founding of the [[European Parliamentary Union]] (EPU), a nominally private organization that held its preliminary conference on 4\u20135 July at Gstaad, Switzerland, and followed it with its first full conference from 8 to 12 September. Speaking at the first EPU conference, Coudenhove-Kalergi argued that the constitution of a wide market with a stable currency was the vehicle for Europe to reconstruct its potential and take the place it deserves within the concert of Nations. On less guarded occasions he was heard to advocate a revival of [[Charlemagne]]'s empire.<ref>{{harvnb|Lipgens|Loth|1988}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eJa0QAQiKNsC&pg=PA537 p. 537]</ref> In 1950 he received the first annual ''[[Karlspreis]]'' (Charlemagne Award), given by the German city of [[Aachen]] to people who contributed to the European idea and European peace. In Japan, a politician [[Ichir\u014d Hatoyama]] was influenced by Coudenhove-Kalergi's fraternity in his book ''The Totalitarian State Against Man''. It was translated into Japanese by Hatoyama and published in 1952. Coudenhove-Kalergi was appointed the honorary chairman of the fraternal youth association that Hatoyama, with the influence of his book, had established in 1953.\n\nIn 1955, he proposed the [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s \"[[Ode to Joy]]\" as the music for the [[European Anthem]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coe.int/t/dgal/dit/ilcd/Historical_Content/hymn/kalergi1.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108214702/http://www.coe.int/t/dgal/dit/ilcd/Historical_Content/hymn/kalergi1.pdf |archivedate=8 November 2008 |title=Union Paneurop\u00e9enne |date=3 August 1955|language= French}} ([http://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/exchange_of_letters_between_richard_coudenhove_kalergi_and_paul_m_g_levy_3_august_1955_to_5_september_1955-en-34a3b196-9a23-4e9e-a977-94e31495b169.html digital document] by [[Centre virtuel de la connaissance sur l'Europe|CVCE]])</ref> a suggestion that the [[Council of Europe]] took up 16 years later.\n\nIn the 1960s, Coudenhove-Kalergi urged Austria to pursue \"an active policy of peace\", as a \"fight against the [[Cold War]] and its continuation, the atomic war\". He advocated Austrian involvement in world politics in order to keep the peace, as \"active neutrality\". He continued his advocacy of European unification in memoranda circulated to the governments of the Federal Republic of Germany, France, the United Kingdom, and Italy. He recommended negotiations between the [[European Community]] and the [[European Free Trade Association]] towards forming a \"European customs union\" that would be free of political and military connections, but would eventually adopt a monetary union.\n\n== Views on race and religion ==\nIn his attitudes towards race and religion, Coudenhove-Kalergi continued the work of his father. In his youth, the elder Coudenhove-Kalergi was an [[antisemitism|antisemite]]. He had expected to confirm his antipathy towards the Jews when he started working on his treatise ''Das Wesen des Antisemitismus'' (''The Essence of Antisemitism''); but, Coudenhove-Kalergi came to a different conclusion by the time he published his book in 1901. Following an [[irony|ironic]] critique of the new racial theories, he declared that the essence of antisemitism amounted to nothing more credible than fanatical religious hatred. He traced that fanaticism to religious bigotry that originated in the promulgation of [[Torah]] under [[Ezra]]. According to the elder Coudenhove-Kalergi, Jewish religious bigotry provoked opposition from the relatively tolerant Greco-Roman [[polytheism|polytheists]], eliciting their anti-Judaic reaction. Heinrich Coudenhove-Kalergi credited the Jews with originating religious intolerance, and condemned it as a violation of genuine religious principles. He branded every sort of anti-Judaism unchristian. He further urged liberal Christians and Jews to ally in protecting both of their religions, and religion as such, against the emerging menace of [[secularism]].<ref>{{harvnb|Langmuir}}, [https://archive.org/details/historyreligiona0000lang/page/22 pp. 22\u201324]; {{harvnb|Johnston|1983|pp=320\u2013321}}</ref>\n\nDespite his opposition to simplistic racial theory, Heinrich Coudenhove-Kalergi agreed that Jews are racially distinct. Although he pointed out that there is no Semitic race, because Semitic is an ethno-linguistic group, he equivocated by also remarking that the charges that Semites were uncreative were belied by civilizations formed by the [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] and [[Babylonians]], who spoke [[Semitic languages]]. He further sought to defend the Jews against charges of parasitic greed and cowardice with anecdotal counterexamples of Jewish industriousness and martial courage.<ref>{{harvnb|Robertson|1999|pp=198\u2013199}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview in the first Pan-European Congress in 1926, Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi expressed the support of Jews by the Pan-European movement and the benefits to Jews with the elimination of racial hatred and economic rivalry brought by the United States of Europe.<ref>{{citation |date= 5 October 1926|title= Jews Participate in Pan-europe Congress Sessions in Vienna|publisher= [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]|url= http://www.jta.org/1926/10/05/archive/jews-participate-in-pan-europe-congress-sessions-in-vienna|accessdate= 5 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi composed a preface for a new edition of his father's condemnation of antisemitism, reissued by his own publishing house. In 1933, he responded to the ascendance of [[Nazism]] by collaborating with [[Heinrich Mann]], [[Arthur Holitscher]], [[Lion Feuchtwanger]], and [[Max Brod]] in writing and publishing the pamphlet ''Gegen die Phrase vom j\u00fcdischen Sch\u00e4dling'' (Against the Phrase '[[Jewish parasite|Jewish Parasite]]').\n\n== Journeys to Japan ==\n=== First return to Japan ===\nThe Pan-European idea influenced a young Japanese diplomat \u2013 in the future, the president of [[Kajima Corporation]] \u2013 [[Morinosuke Kajima]] during his residence in Berlin in 1922.<ref name=\"Hirakawa\">{{harvnb|Hirakawa|2011|pp=40\u201342}}</ref> Coudenhove-Kalergi formed a friendship with Kajima and then asked him to translate the book ''Pan-Europa'' into Japanese.<ref name=\"Hirakawa\" /> He proposed Pan-Asia to Kajima and promised to give [[Dutch East Indies]] as their friendship after the realization of the task to establish Pan-Asia.<ref name=\"Hirakawa\" /> Kajima published ''Pan-Europa'' in Japanese in 1927. In 1930 Kajima retired from the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] to become [[Member of parliament|MP]]. His ambition to become an MP was due to Coudenhove-Kalergi's influence.<ref>{{harvnb|Tozawa|2013c}}, [http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/RCKjap1-3.htm chpt. (3)]</ref> In 1970\u20131971 he published the complete works of Coudenhove-Kalergi from Kajima Institute Publishing that was established by Morinosuke Kajima. He respected Coudenhove-Kalergi over a lifetime, dreaming of the realization of Pan-Asia.<ref name=\"Hirakawa\" />\n\nIn Japan, the Pan-European idea also influenced a journalist [[Yoshinori Maeda]], the president of [[NHK]]. He became a pioneer of [[Asia-Pacific Broadcasting Union]] with the image of ''Pan-Europa'' that he read in his student days.<ref>{{harvnb|Tozawa|2013c}}, [http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/RCKjap1-2.htm chpt. (2)]</ref>\n\nIn 1953 Ichir\u014d Hatoyama established Yuai Youth Association (later Yuai Association), the fraternal association as the successor of fraternity that Coudenhove-Kalergi mentioned in ''The Totalitarian State Against Man''. The Japanese word {{nihongo|''y\u016bai''|[[wikt:\u53cb\u611b|\u53cb\u611b]]}} has several meanings but especially the word used by Hatoyama means ''fraternity'' and in German ''[[wikt:Br\u00fcderlichkeit|br\u00fcderlichkeit]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Pempel|Lee|2012}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=umb2lVHU81IC&pg=PA137 p. 137]</ref> It can also be considered equivalent to \"[[Libert\u00e9, \u00e9galit\u00e9, fraternit\u00e9|Liberty, Equality, Fraternity]]\" (Brotherhood), the motto of the French Republic. An educator [[Kaoru Hatoyama]] became the second president of the association after her husband Ichir\u014d, the first president, died in 1959.\n\nIn 1967 Coudenhove-Kalergi was awarded the Kajima Peace Award, and was invited to Japan by Morinosuke Kajima as the president of Kajima Institute of International Peace, Yoshinori Maeda as the president of NHK, and Kaoru Hatoyama as the president of Yuai Youth Association. Together with his second wife Alexandra in a wheelchair,<ref>{{cite web |year= 2013|url= http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/RCKjap0.htm|script-title=ja:\u30af\u30fc\u30c7\u30f3\u30db\u30fc\u30d5\u30fb\u30ab\u30ec\u30eb\u30ae\u30fc\u3068\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u95a2\u4fc2|last1=Tozawa|first1=Hidenori|publisher= Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi Forum (School of Law, Tohoku University)|accessdate=17 November 2014|language=Japanese | ref= harv}}</ref> Coudenhove-Kalergi stayed in Japan from 26 October to 8 November. He was also accompanied by his young brother [[Gerolf Coudenhove-Kalergi|Gerolf]]'s daughter [[Barbara Coudenhove-Kalergi|Barbara]].<ref>{{harvnb|Tozawa|2013c}}, [http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/RCKjap1-5.htm chpt. (5)]</ref> Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi was also awarded ''First Order of the Sacred Treasure'' of Japan. He was granted an audience with the Emperor [[Hirohito]], [[Empress K\u014djun]], their son Crown Prince [[Akihito]] to whom he had presented his book in 1953 in Switzerland, and Crown Princess [[Empress Michiko|Michiko]]. This time, he had returned to Japan for the first time since his childhood 71 years earlier. He gave several lectures and met various leaders. Coudenhove-Kalergi spent 2 weeks in Japan as a guest of Japanese TV, radio, newspaper, magazines and other media.<ref name=\"kajima peace award\">{{harvnb|Kajima MONTHLY REPORT DIGEST|2005}}</ref> While in Japan, Coudenhove-Kalergi specifically asked for a meeting with the president of [[Soka Gakkai]], Dr. [[Daisaku Ikeda]], as Coudenhove-Kalergi had been interested in Ikeda's work for many years. After their first meeting in October 1967, Coudenhove-Kalergi described Ikeda as \"very energetic, life-loving, honorable, friendly and intelligent.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Tozawa|2013d}}, [http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/RCKjap3.htm chpt. (1)]</ref>\n\n=== Soka Gakkai invitation ===\nCoudenhove-Kalergi visited Japan again at the invitation of the Soka Gakkai in October 1970.<ref name=\"Tozawa2013d\">{{harvnb|Tozawa|2013d}}, [http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/RCKjap3-2.htm chpt. (2)]</ref> During his stay, he and [[Daisaku Ikeda]] conducted a formal dialogue over the course of several days, a total of more than 12 hours of which was recorded for posterity.<ref>{{cite web|date= 19 November 1978|url= http://www.seikyoonline.jp/ecorepo/teigen/kadai.html|script-title= ja:\u74b0\u5883\u5831\u544a\u66f82012: \u74b0\u5883\u554f\u984c\u306f\u5168\u4eba\u985e\u7684\u306a\u8ab2\u984c|last1= Ikeda|first1= Daisaku|publisher= SEIKYO online ([[Seikyo Shimbun]])|accessdate= 17 November 2014|language= Japanese|ref= harv|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141129040853/http://www.seikyoonline.jp/ecorepo/teigen/kadai.html|archivedate= 29 November 2014}}</ref> He also visited the campus of [[S\u014dka University|Soka University]] in Tokyo, which was under construction at that time.<ref name=\"Tozawa2013d\" />\n\nTwo decades later, in 1990, Ikeda proposed that Coudenhove-Kalergi's favorite song, Beethoven's \"Ode to Joy,\" be regularly performed at major Soka Gakkai meetings. It was reported in Japan that this was one cause of the split between the Soka Gakkai and [[Soka Gakkai International]] (SGI) from [[Nichiren Sh\u014dsh\u016b|Nichiren Shoshu]] in 1991, as the Nichiren Shoshu priesthood objected to the song's \"Christian origins.\"\n\n== Death ==\n[[File:Coudenhove-Park.Hofpavillon.U4hietzing.A.JPG|thumb|Coudenhove-Park at [[Hietzing]], Vienna]]\n\nAccording to a masonic report, Coudenhove-Kalergi died of a stroke.<ref>{{harvnb|Zuber|1995}}</ref> His secretary, however, indicated that Coudenhove-Kalergi possibly committed suicide. In the memoir his secretary wrote, she said his death had been kept secret so as not to disappoint those who considered him to be the great visionary of European integration.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dw.de/27112001-\u043f\u0430\u043d-\u0435\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435-\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435-\u0434\u043e\u043a\u0443\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b/a-444966|script-title=ru:\u041f\u0430\u043d-\u0435\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435: \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0443\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b|last1= Huseynov|first1= Hasan|date= 27 November 2001|language= Russian|publisher= [[Deutsche Welle]]|accessdate=31 October 2014}}</ref> Coudenhove-Kalergi was the head of the Pan-European Union until his death. The presidency was succeeded by Otto von Habsburg.\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi is buried at [[Gruben/Meiden|Gruben]] near [[Gstaad]].<ref>{{harvnb|Jilek||p=208}}</ref> His grave, covered with [[wild grape]]s, is located in a [[Japanese rock garden]] in the [[Swiss Alps]]. The grave is unpretentious and upon it is the French epitaph \"{{Lang|fr|Pionnier des \u00c9tats-Unis d'Europe}}\" (Pioneer of the United States of Europe), with none of the other great titles that many supporters believe he had earned.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.businessmir.ch/?p=153327&language=en|title= COUNT COUDENHOVE-KALERGI: SWITZERLAND AS THE MODEL OF EUROPEAN UNITY|last1= Aizpurvit|first1= Katerina|date= June 2011|publisher= [[Business Mir]]|accessdate=31 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nCoudenhove-Kalergi was married three times: to [[Ida Roland]] (1881\u20131951), to Alexandra Gr\u00e4fin von Tiele-Winkler (1896\u20131968), and to Melanie Benatzky-Hoffmann (1909\u20131983). His known children were Ida's daughter Erika and Alexandra's son Alexander, both of whom were his step-children.<ref>{{harvnb|Pernhorst|2008|p=38}}</ref>\n\n== Quotes ==\n{{Clear}}\n{{quote|{{Lang|de|Jedes gro\u00dfe historische Geschehen begann als Utopie und endete als Realit\u00e4t.}}\n\n(Translation:) Every great historical event began as a utopia and ended as a reality.\n| title = ''Pan-Europa'' (''Pan-Europe'')<ref>{{cite book |last= Coudenhove-Kalergi|first= Richard Nikolaus|title= Pan-Europe|url= https://books.google.com/?id=vz7zAAAAMAAJ|publisher= Pan-Europa-Verlag|language= German|date= 1923|quote= [https://books.google.com/books?&id=vz7zAAAAMAAJ&q=Jedes+gro\u00dfe+historische+Geschehen+begann+als+Utopie+und+endete+als+Realit\u00e4t. Jedes gro\u00dfe historische Geschehen begann als Utopie und endete als Realit\u00e4t.]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Coudenhove-Kalergi|first= Richard Nikolaus|title= Pan-Europe|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=zwDPAAAAMAAJ|date= 1926|quote= [https://books.google.com/books?id=zwDPAAAAMAAJ&q=Every+great+political+happening+began+as+a+Utopia+and+ended+as+a+Reality. Every great political happening began as a Utopia and ended as a Reality.]}} ([https://books.google.com/books?id=xUdLAAAAMAAJ&q=Every+great+political+happening+began+as+a+Utopia+and+ended+as+a+Reality. Knopf's other version in 1926 on Google Books])</ref>\n| author = Richard N. Coudenhove-Kalergi}}\n{{quote\n| text = We are experiencing the most dangerous revolution in world history: the revolution of the State against man. We are experiencing the worst idolatry of all time: the deification of the state.\n| title= ''Totaler Staat \u2013 Totaler Mensch'' (''The Totalitarian State Against Man'')\n| author = Richard N. Coudenhove-Kalergi}}\n{{quote\n| text = One actual step forward is worth more than a thousand imagined steps.\n| title= ''Totaler Staat \u2013 Totaler Mensch'' (''The Totalitarian State Against Man'')\n| author = Richard N. Coudenhove-Kalergi}}\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''Adel'' (1922)\n* ''Ethik und Hyperethik'' (1922); ''H\u00e9ros ou Saint'' (1929), the Cahiers Internationaux series of the publisher Les Editions Rieder, 7, Place Saint-Sulpice, Paris, translated from German into French by Marcel Beaufils\n* ''Pan-Europ]'' (1923), Paneuropa Verlag; ''Pan-Europe'' (1926), [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]], abridged, with an introduction by [[Nicholas Murray Butler]]\n* ''Krise der Weltanschauung'' (1923)\n* ''Pazifismus'' (1924)\n* ''Deutschlands Europ\u00e4ische Sendung. Ein Gespr\u00e4ch'' (1924)\n* ''Praktischer Idealismus'' (1925)\n* ''Kampf um Paneuropa'' (3 Volumes, 1925\u201328)\n* ''Held oder Heiliger'' (1927)\n* ''Br\u00fcning \u2013 Hitler: Revision der B\u00fcndnispolitik'' (1931), Paneuropa-Verlag\n* ''Stalin & Co.'' (1931)\n* ''Gebote des Lebens'' (1931)\n* ''Los vom Materialismus!'' (1931)\n* ''La lutte pour l'Europe'' (1931)\n* ''Revolution durch Technik'' (1932)\n* ''Gegen die Phrase vom j\u00fcdischen Sch\u00e4dling'' (1933), co-authored with [[Heinrich Mann]], [[Arthur Holitscher]], [[Lion Feuchtwanger]], and [[Max Brod]]\n* ''Europa erwacht!'' (1934)\n* ''Judenha\u00df von heute: Graf H. Coudenhofe-Kalergi. Das Wesen des Antisemitismus'' (1935)\n* ''Europa ohne Elend: Ausgew\u00e4hlte Reden'' (1936)\n* ''Judenha\u00df!'' (1937)\n* ''Totaler Staat \u2013 Totaler Mensch'' (1937), Paneuropa Verlag; ''Totaler Mensch \u2013 Totaler Staat'' (1939), Herold Verlag; ''Totaler Mensch \u2013 Totaler Staat'' (1965), Herold Verlag\n* ''The Totalitarian State Against Man'', with an introduction by [[Wickham Steed]], translated by Sir [[Andrew McFadyean|Andrew Mc Fadyean]] (1938), London, Frederick Muller Ltd.\n* ''Europe Must Unite'', translated by Sir Andrew Mc Fadyean (1939)\n* ''Die europ\u00e4ische Mission der Frau'' (1940)\n* ''Crusade for Pan-Europe'' (1943)\n* ''Kampf um Europa'' (1949)\n* ''Ida Roland: In Memoriam'' (1951)\n* ''Die Europ\u00e4ische Nation'' (1953)\n* ''Der Gentleman'' (1953)\n* ''An Idea Conquers the World'', with a preface by Winston S. Churchill (1953)\n* ''Vom Ewigen Krieg zum Gro\u00dfen Frieden'' (1956)\n* ''Eine Idee erobert Europa'' (1958)\n* ''From War to Peace'' (1959)\n* ''Ein Leben f\u00fcr Europa'' (1966)\n* ''F\u00fcr die Revolution der Br\u00fcderlichkeit'' (1968), Zurich, Verlag Die Waage\n* {{nihongo|''Bi no Kuni \u2013 Nihon heno Kikyou ''|{{Abbr|\u7f8e\u306e\u56fd|Country of Beauty}} \u2013 {{Abbr|\u65e5\u672c\u3078\u306e\u5e30\u90f7|Homecoming to Japan}}}}, translated into Japanese by Morinosuke Kajima (1968), Tokyo, Kajima Institute Publishing\n* ''Weltmacht Europa'' (1971)\n* {{nihongo|''Bunmei \u2013 Nishi to Higashi''|{{Abbr|\u6587\u660e|Civilization}} \u2013 {{Abbr|\u897f\u3068\u6771|West and East}}}}, interview collection with Daisaku Ikeda (1972), Tokyo, publication branch of [[Sankei Shimbun]] Co., Ltd.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n* 1950: [[Charlemagne Prize]]\n* 1954: [[Legion of Honour|Officer of the Legion of Honour]]<ref name=\"Kosch\">{{harvnb|Kosch|2003}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=NmR_GZTZOecC&pg=PA2064 p. 374]</ref>\n* 1962: [[Decoration of Honour for Services to the Republic of Austria|Grand Decoration of Honour in Silver with Star of the Republic of Austria]]\n* 1965: [[Sonning Prize]]\n* 1966: {{lang|de|Europ\u00e4ischer Karlspreis der Sudetendeutschen Landsmannschaft}}\n* 1967: [[Order of the Sacred Treasure|Order of the Sacred Treasure, 1st class of Japan]]\n* 1967: [[Kajima]] Peace Award<ref name=\"kajima peace award\" />\n* 1972: [[Konrad Adenauer Prize]]\n* 1972: [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany|Knight Commander's Cross of the Federal Republic of Germany]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kas.de/wf/de/71.12596/ |title=Tabellarischer Lebenslauf: Richard Nikolaus Graf Coudenhove-Kalergi |language=German|publisher=[[Konrad Adenauer Foundation|Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung]] |accessdate= 27 January 2015|date=27 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kas.de/wf/de/71.11513/ |title=Coudenhove-Kalergi, Richard Nikolaus Graf  |language=German|publisher=Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung |accessdate= 27 January 2015|date=18 July 2012  }}</ref>\n* [[Honorary degree|Dr. h. c.]] of [[Nihon University]]<ref name=\"Kosch\" />\n* {{lang|de|Ehrenb\u00fcrgerw\u00fcrde der Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt a. M.}}<ref>{{harvnb|Duchhardt|2005}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=BPjFiEV1PDQC&pg=PA306 p. 306]</ref>\n* [[Nobel Peace Prize]] nominee in 42 nominations, known by 1963 so far.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show_people.php?id=1991 |title=Count Richard Nicolas Coudenhove-Kalergi |publisher=Official web site of the Nobel Prize |accessdate= 27 January 2015}}</ref> 1964\u20131972 period is still concealed.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Federal Europe]]\n* [[Ideas of European unity before 1945]]\n* [[Pan-European nationalism]]\n* [[Founding fathers of the European Union]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |year= 2013a|url= http://www.law.tohoku.ac.jp/~tozawa/RCK%20HP/mitsuko0.htm|script-title=ja:\u30df\u30c4\u30b3\u30fb\u30af\u30fc\u30c7\u30f3\u30db\u30fc\u30d5\u30fb\u30ab\u30ec\u30eb\u30ae\u30fc (\u9752\u5c71\u5149\u5b50)|last1=Tozawa|first1=Hidenori|publisher= Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi Forum (School of Law, [[Tohoku University]])|accessdate=31 October 2014|language=Japanese | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web |year= 2013b|url= http://www.law.tohoku.a