=31 August 2015 |work=[[Kungumam (magazine)|Kungumam]] |access-date=10 May 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511052745/http://kungumam.co.in/newkungumam/VArticalinnerdetail.aspx?id=5677&id1=43&issue=20150831 |archive-date=11 May 2016 |language=Tamil |trans-title=The Path Kattabomman took!}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Pyramids TNIE\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Veerapandiya-Kattabomman-Conquered-Land-of-Pyramids/2015/08/22/article2987210.ece |title=Veerapandiya Kattabomman 'Conquered' Land of Pyramids |last=Manigandan |first=K. R. |date=22 August 2015 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=22 August 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822132835/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Veerapandiya-Kattabomman-Conquered-Land-of-Pyramids/2015/08/22/article2987210.ece |archive-date=22 August 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Thrill\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Kattabomman-to-Thrill-Once-Again/2015/03/21/article2723012.ece |title=Kattabomman to Thrill Once Again |date=21 March 2015 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=25 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326123314/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Kattabomman-to-Thrill-Once-Again/2015/03/21/article2723012.ece |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=otJDRkUxKGwC |title=Adoor Gopalakrishnan: A Life in Cinema |last=Bhaskaran |first=Gautaman |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-670-08171-4 |location=India |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XgrKSAAACAAJ |title=Cinemas of South India: Culture, Resistance, and Ideology |last=Dechamma C. C. |first=Sowmya |last2=Prakash |first2=Elavarthi Sathya |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-19-806795-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Autobiography of an Actor: Sivaji Ganesan, October 1928&nbsp;\u2013 July 2001 |title-link=Autobiography of an Actor |last=Ganesan |first=Sivaji |last2=Narayana Swamy |first2=T. S. |publisher=Sivaji Prabhu Charities Trust |year=2007 |location=Chennai |oclc=297212002 |ref=harv |author-link=Sivaji Ganesan |orig-year=2002}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Starlight, Starbright: The Early Tamil Cinema |last=Guy |first=Randor |publisher=Amra Publishers |year=1997 |location=Chennai |oclc=52794531 |ref=harv |author-link=Randor Guy}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://indiancine.ma/texts/indiancine.ma%3AEncyclopedia_of_Indian_Cinema/text.pdf |title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Cinema |last=Rajadhyaksha |first=Ashish |last2=Willemen |first2=Paul |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year=1998 |isbn=0-19-563579-5 |ref=harv |orig-year=1994}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UKWeAwAAQBAJ |title=MGR: A Biography |last=Veeravalli |first=Shrikanth |publisher=Rupa Publications |year=2013 |isbn=978-8-1291-3228-4 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0250803|title=Veerapandiya Kattabomman}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|1950s|India}}\n{{B. R. Panthulu}}\n{{NationalFilmAwardBestFeatureFilmTamil}}\n\n[[Category:1950s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:1959 films]]\n[[Category:Action films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about royalty]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Epic films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films directed by B. R. Panthulu]]\n[[Category:Films scored by G. Ramanathan]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1790s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the British Raj]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Historical epic films]]\n[[Category:History of India on film]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian biographical films]]\n[[Category:Indian films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian historical films]]\n[[Category:Indian war films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1959 film by B. R. Panthulu}}\n{{For|the 1993 film|Kattabomman (film)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Veerapandiya Kattabomman\n| image          = Veerapandiya Kattabomman Poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[B. R. Panthulu]]\n| producer       = B. R. Panthulu\n| story          = [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' (play)}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Sivaji Ganesan]]\n*[[Gemini Ganesan]]\n*[[Padmini (actress)|Padmini]]\n*[[S. Varalakshmi]]\n*[[Ragini (actress)|Ragini]]\n}}\n| music          = [[G. Ramanathan]]\n| cinematography = W. R. Subbarao\n| editing        = R. Devarajan\n| studio         = Padmini Pictures\n| distributor    = Padmini Pictures\n| released       = {{film date|1959|5|10|London|1959|5|16|Tamil Nadu|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 201&nbsp;minutes{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=361}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n'''''Veerapandiya Kattabomman''''' ({{trans|Kattabomman, the Brave Warrior}}) is a 1959&nbsp;Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] [[biographical film|biographical]] [[war film]] produced and directed by [[B. R. Panthulu]]. The film stars [[Sivaji Ganesan]], [[Gemini Ganesan]], [[Padmini (actress)|Padmini]], [[S. Varalakshmi]], and [[Ragini (actress)|Ragini]], with [[V. K. Ramasamy (actor)|V. K. Ramasamy]] and [[Javar Seetharaman]] in supporting roles. Its soundtrack and score were composed by [[G. Ramanathan]].\n\nProduced and distributed by Panthulu under his banner Padmini Pictures, the film is loosely based on the story of [[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]], the 18th-century South Indian chieftain who rebelled against the [[East India Company]]. It was an adaptation of the play of the same name by [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]] which featured Sivaji Ganesan as the title character, and premiered in August 1957. [[Principal photography]] began in October the same year, and took place mainly in [[Jaipur]] and Madras (now [[Chennai]]) till late 1958. This was the first Tamil film released in [[Technicolor]].\n\n''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' premiered in London on 10 May 1959, and was released in [[Tamil Nadu]] six days later. It was critically acclaimed; Sivaji Ganesan's performance as Kattabomman received widespread praise, although some film scholars considered elements in the film, particularly the portrayal of the title character, to be historically inaccurate. It was a commercial success, running for over 25 weeks in theatres and becoming a [[silver jubilee]] film. ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' was dubbed and released in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] as ''Veerapandiya Kattabrahmanna'' in the same year, and in [[Hindi]] as ''Amar Shaheed'' the following year.\n\nThe film was the first in Tamil cinema to receive international awards for Best Film, Best Actor, and Best Music Director at the 1960 Afro-Asian Film Festival in Cairo, and received a Certificate of Merit as part of the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Tamil]]. ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' was re-released in 1984, and a digitally-restored version was released on 21 August 2015; both were commercially successful.\n\n== Plot ==\n[[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]], the [[Tribal chief|chieftain]] of [[Panchalankurichi]], is a brave warrior. On receiving news of a robbery in his territory, he and his retinue set out incognito to capture the robbers. When captured, the robbers confess that they had been hired by the [[British Raj|British]] to create unrest in Kattabomman's domain; the British had enticed the neighbouring chieftain, [[Ettappan]], to help them annexe Panchalankurichi.\n\nVellaiyammal, who lives in [[Chalakudy|Chayalkudi]], a village near Panchalankurichi, vows to marry the man who tames her pet bull. She brings her bull to Panchalankurichi for participating in a [[jallikattu]] game sponsored by Kattabomman. All those who attempt to tame the bull fail until Vellaiyathevan, Kattabomman's commander-in-chief, subdues the bull and wins Vellaiyammal's love. Kattabomman later learns of their love, and encourages them to marry.\n\nThe king receives a message from W. C. Jackson, the tax collector for [[Tirunelveli]], which demands a meeting with him at [[Ramanathapuram]] to discuss payment. Captain Davison, Kattabomman's British friend, advises him to see Jackson. Jackson, learning that Kattabomman has come with his troops, demands to meet him alone. At the meeting, Jackson insults him and orders him arrested. Surrounded by British troops, Kattabomman fights and escapes; however, his minister Thanapathi Sivasubramaniam Pillai is captured.\n\nSome time later, Pillai is released and brings news that Jackson has been sent back to England at Davison's recommendation. A British messenger sent to Kattabomman's court by Colonel S. R. Lushington, Tirunelveli's new revenue collector reports that Pillai and his men have looted their granaries and killed their men at [[Srivaikuntam]]. Pillai justifies his act, saying that he instructed his men to do it because of the famine in their kingdom. Ashamed of Pillai's action, Kattabomman accuses him of theft and murder. Pillai apologises and offers himself as a prisoner to the British, but Kattabomman refuses to hand him over; instead, he offers money to compensate for the looted rice. Lushington refuses the compensation and, with Major Bannerman's and Ettappan's help, incites the neighbouring rulers to attack Kattabomman. Bannerman is placed in charge of the British troops; he and Ettappan plan to attack Panchalankurichi when the people are attending a festival in Tiruchendur. Kattabomman's spy Sundaralingam informs the king, who prepares for war.\n\nOn the day of the battle, Vellaiyammal begs Vellaiyathevan not to go because she had a nightmare full of evil omens the previous night. Ignoring her entreaties, Vellaiyathevan sets out and is killed in the ensuing battle. When she learns of her husband's death, Vellaiyammal avenges him by killing the man who killed him. She finds Vellaiyathevan's body and, overcome by grief, falls dead across it. Bannerman's troops attack Panchalankurichi with heavy artillery, and Kattabomman's army suffers. The king, wounded in the neck, is saved by his brother [[Oomaithurai]]. Sensing that the fort cannot survive another cannon barrage, Kattabomman and Oomaithurai flee to the adjoining kingdom of [[Kovilpatti]]. Pillai, disguising himself as Kattabomman, decoys the British soldiers who are on the king's trail. From Kovilpatti, Kattabomman and Oomaithurai flee to [[Pudukkottai]]. Thondaimaan, the king of Pudukkottai, is ordered by the British to capture Kattabomman and Oomaithurai. Fearing the British, Thondaimaan captures them and hands them over. While Oomaithurai is jailed, Kattabomman is tried by the British and hanged.\n\n== Cast ==\n:''Note: Listing as per the film's opening credits.''<ref name=\"Credits\" />\n{{Col-begin|width=70%}}\n{{col-break|width=50%}}\n* [[Sivaji Ganesan]] as [[Veerapandiya Kattabomman|Kattabomman]]\n* [[Gemini Ganesan]] as Vellaiyadhevan\n* [[Padmini (actress)|Padmini]] as Vellaiyammal\n* [[S. Varalakshmi]] as Jakkammal\n* [[Ragini (actress)|Ragini]] as Sundaravadivu\n* [[V. K. Ramasamy (actor)|V. K. Ramasamy]] as [[Ettappan|Ettappa Nayagar]]\n* [[Javar Seetharaman]] as Bannerman\n* [[O. A. K. Thevar]] as [[Oomaithurai]]\n* M. R. Santhanam as Dhanapathi Subramania Pillai\n* [[Kula Deivam V. R. Rajagopal|V. R. Rajagopal]] as Kariyappan \n* [[A. Karunanidhi]] as Sundaralingam \n* Pakkirisami as Ponnan\n{{col-break|width=50%}}\n* Chinaiah as Adappakkaran\n* Stunt Somu as Gopal Iyer\n* K. V. Seenivasan as Dubash Ramalinga Mudaliar  \n* Anandan as Duraisingam\n* Natarajan as Colonel Maxwell \n* S. A. Kannan as Captain Davison\n* [[C. R. Parthiban|Parthiban]] as W. C. Jackson\n* Krishnasami as Alan\n* Kannan as Governor\n* [[T. P. Muthulakshmi|Muthulakshmi]] as Kamakshi\n* [[Tambaram Lalitha]] as Valli\n* Baby Kanchana as Baby Meena\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Origin ===\nSince childhood, [[Sivaji Ganesan]] dreamt of playing the resistance fighter [[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]]; he had left home at age seven to fulfill his dream.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mayyam.com/talk/showthread.php?8593-Nadigar-Thilagam-Sivaji-Ganesan-Part-9/page45 |title=\u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0baa\u0bca\u0bae\u0bcd\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bc8 |date=17 October 1999 |work=[[Dina Thanthi]] |access-date=22 May 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20170517075620/http://www.mayyam.com/talk/showthread.php?8593-Nadigar-Thilagam-Sivaji-Ganesan-Part-9/page45 |archive-date=17 May 2017 |trans-title=Kattabomman Postal Stamp}}</ref> Several years later, while Ganesan and writer [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]]{{efn|Sivaji Ganesan had been on the payroll of a theatre group, owned by Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy, named Sakthi Nataka Sabha. Krishnasamy had encouraged Sivaji Ganesan in his early days on the stage.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p=283}}}} were travelling through [[Kayatharu]], where Kattabomman was hanged, Ganesan expressed a desire to produce a [[Play (theatre)|play]] based on Kattabomman's life; his first exposure to acting was when he saw ''Kambalaththaar Kooththu'', a [[street theatre|street play]] about Kattabomman's life. Krishnasamy immediately agreed, and began to write a script. Krishnasamy completed writing the script within a month.<ref name=\"Kattabomman\" /> Krishnasamy's play, ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'', premiered in [[Salem district|Salem]] in late August 1957 and was performed by Ganesan's troupe, Sivaji Nataka Mandram.<ref name=\"Kattabomman\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dinamalar.com/supplementary_detail.asp?id=23081&ncat=2 |title=\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b95\u0ba4\u0bc8!&nbsp;\u2013 \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0b9c\u0bbf \u0b95\u0ba3\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd (11) |date=14 December 2014 |work=[[Dinamalar]] |access-date=25 September 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180925062700/http://www.dinamalar.com/supplementary_detail.asp?id=23081&ncat=2 |archive-date=25 September 2018 |trans-title=Story of the hero!&nbsp;\u2013 Sivaji Ganesan (11)}}</ref> He had invested nearly {{INR}}{{formatnum:50000}}{{efn|The exchange rate in 1958 was 4.79 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) to one dollar (US$).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/rupees-journey-since-independence-down-by-65-times-against-dollar/articleshow/22025032.cms |title=Rupee's journey since Independence: Down by 65 times against dollar |date=24 August 2013 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=23 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130829085318/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-24/news/41444029_1_indian-rupee-american-currency-continued-dollar-demand |archive-date=29 August 2013}}</ref>|name = exchange1958}} for sets and costumes.<ref name=\"Kattabomman\" /> When he saw the play, director [[B. R. Panthulu]] decided to adapt it as a feature film.<ref name=\"Kattabomman\" /> Panthulu produced the film version (also entitled ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'') with his company, Padmini Pictures.{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=361}}<ref name=\"roar\" /> G. Dharmarajan, the play's set designer, was also assigned the same crew position for the film.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/art-grand-and-eloquent/article2834203.ece |title=Art grand and eloquent |last=Shivapprasadh |first=S. |date=26 January 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220144643/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/art-grand-and-eloquent/article2834203.ece |archive-date=20 February 2015}}</ref> W. R. Subbarao was signed as cinematographer, and R. Devarajan as editor.<ref name=\"Nadigarthilagam.com\" /> The screenplay was credited to a \"history research team\", headed by [[M. P. Sivagnanam]] and consisting of Krishnasamy, Panthulu, Sivaji Ganesan, P. A. Kumar and Singamuthu.<ref name=\"Nadigarthilagam.com\" />\n\nBefore Ganesan and Panthulu, there were two unsuccessful attempts to make a film on Kattabomman: in July 1948,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/21252 |title=\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0bae\u0bbe\u0bae\u0ba3\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0bae\u0ba9\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u2018\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bb2\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2 \u0ba8\u0bbf\u0b9c\u0bae\u0bcd\u2019&nbsp;\u2013 59 {{!}} \u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0baa\u0bca\u0bae\u0bcd\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0b9f\u0bae\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b85\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbf\u0baf \u0b9a\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bc8 \u0baa\u0bc2\u0ba4\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd! |last=Vamanan |date=16 January 2017 |work=[[Dinamalar]] |access-date=9 November 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109102857/http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/web/news/21252 |archive-date=9 November 2018 |location=Nellai |author-link=Vamanan}}</ref> Selvam Pictures announced its intention to produce ''Kattabommu'' (the rebel's real name), which would star [[P. U. Chinnappa]].{{Sfn|Guy|1997|pages=281\u2013282}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vikatan.com/news/coverstory/60547-pu-chinnappatamil-cinema-pioneers-series-24.html |title=10 \u0bb5\u0bc7\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbf.\u0baf\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe ! (\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bcb\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd-\u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd 24) |last=Balakrishnan |first=V. |date=14 March 2018 |work=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |access-date=8 April 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408080545/https://www.vikatan.com/news/coverstory/60547-pu-chinnappatamil-cinema-pioneers-series-24.html |archive-date=8 April 2018 |trans-title=P. U. Chinnappa was the first actor to play 10 roles ! (Pioneers of Tamil Cinema-Chapter 24)}}</ref> The other attempt was made by producer [[S. S. Vasan]] of [[Gemini Studios]]; a promotional poster for the project, entitled ''Kattabomman'', was released on 5 November 1953.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mayyam.com/talk/showthread.php?8593-Nadigar-Thilagam-Sivaji-Ganesan-Part-9%2Fpage349 |title=\u0b9c\u0bc6\u0bae\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b85\u0b9f\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0baa\u0b9f\u0bae\u0bcd&nbsp;\u2013 \u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0baa\u0bca\u0bae\u0bcd\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bcd |date=5 November 1953 |work=[[Swadesamitran]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403054358/http://www.mayyam.com/talk/showthread.php?8593-Nadigar-Thilagam-Sivaji-Ganesan-Part-9%2Fpage349 |archive-date=3 April 2015 |language=ta |trans-title=Gemini's next film&nbsp;\u2013 Kattabomman}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19531105&printsec=frontpage |title=Gemini's Next&nbsp;\u2013 Kattabomman |date=5 November 1953 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=10}}</ref> A notice from Gemini, inviting anyone with useful information about Kattabomman and his exploits to send it to the studio's storyboard department, was published three days later in the magazine ''[[Ananda Vikatan]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=8 November 1953 |title=\u0b9c\u0bc6\u0bae\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 |trans-title=Gemini's announcement |magazine=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=ta}}</ref> According to a 1957 article by [[Singapore]]-based ''Indian Movie News'', when Ganesan heard about Vasan's attempt to make a film about Kattabomman, he asked him to abandon the project; Vasan agreed, and lent Ganesan important research material on Kattabomman.<ref name=\"IMN\" /> Film historian [[Randor Guy]] contradicted this in his 1997 book, ''Starlight, Starbright: The Early Tamil Cinema'', saying that writers like [[Kothamangalam Subbu]] and Veppathur Kittoo were hired by Vasan to research Kattabomman's life, and Vasan believed that Ganesan, who had become popular after ''[[Parasakthi (film)|Parasakthi]]'' (1952), was the only eligible choice to portray Kattabomman. Guy noted that Ganesan hesitated to work with Vasan, since he was earlier rejected for a role in ''[[Chandralekha (1948 film)|Chandralekha]]'' (1948), leading to Vasan dropping the project.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|pp=248, 282}} Despite this, Ganesan later appeared in Vasan's later ventures, ''[[Irumbu Thirai]]'' (1960) and ''[[Motor Sundaram Pillai]]'' (1966).{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p=283}}\n\n=== Casting ===\nGanesan originally offered the role of Vellaiyathevan to [[S. S. Rajendran]], who declined due to his commitment to ''[[Sivagangai Seemai]]''.{{Sfn|Ganesan|Narayana Swamy|2007|pages=120\u2013121}} He later asked actress [[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]] to ask her husband, [[Gemini Ganesan]], to play the role.{{Sfn|Ganesan|Narayana Swamy|2007|pages=120\u2013121}} Gemini was initially reluctant to accept the part, feeling it was \"improper\" to replace Rajendran. After Rajendran wrote to Panthulu that he had no objection to Gemini playing Vellaiyathevan, however, the actor agreed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ft.lk/columns/kaadhal-mannan-gemini-ganesan-romantic-actor-king-of-tamil-cinema/4-444263 |title=\"Kaadhal Mannan\" Gemini Ganesan, romantic actor king of Tamil cinema |last=Jeyaraj |first=D. B. S. |date=11 July 2015 |work=[[Daily FT]] |access-date=24 June 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618160709/http://www.ft.lk/columns/kaadhal-mannan-gemini-ganesan-romantic-actor-king-of-tamil-cinema/4-444263 |archive-date=18 June 2018 |author-link=D. B. S. Jeyaraj}}</ref> [[Padmini (actress)|Padmini]] was cast as Vellaiyammal, [[O. A. K. Thevar]] as Oomaithurai, and [[V. K. Ramasamy (actor)|V. K. Ramasamy]] as [[Ettappan]].<ref name=\"Credits\" /> [[S. Varalakshmi]] played Kattabomman's wife, Jakkamma, and was a playback singer.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/S-Varalakshmi-passes-away/articleshow/5048475.cms |title=S Varalakshmi passes away |last=Ravi |first=Bhama Devi |date=24 September 2009 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=25 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XQorwkvD?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/S-Varalakshmi-passes-away/articleshow/5048475.cms |archive-date=31 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nLord W. C. Jackson was played by [[C. R. Parthiban]],<ref name=\"mohanmuses\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/fans-keep-the-legend-alive/article6467476.ece |title=Fans keep the legend alive |last=Naig |first=Udhav |date=2 October 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=25 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325141759/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/fans-keep-the-legend-alive/article6467476.ece |archive-date=25 March 2015}}</ref> [[Javar Seetharaman]] played Major Bannerman,<ref name=\"60 years\" /> and M. R. Santhanam played the minister, Thanapathi Sivasubramaniam Pillai.<ref name=\"Credits\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/a-brief-history-of-nadigar-sangam/article7877460.ece |title=A brief history of Nadigar Sangam |last=Raman |first=Mohan V. |date=14 November 2015 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=14 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614142516/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/a-brief-history-of-nadigar-sangam/article7877460.ece |archive-date=14 June 2016}}</ref> Kattabomman's daughter in the film, Meena (Baby Kanchana),<ref name=\"Credits\" /> was a fictional character created by Krishnasamy. Meena was based on Krishnasamy's daughter, Mynavathi, who died when she was five years old.<ref name=\"Kattabomman\" /> Krishnasamy initially refused to include the scene of Meena's death (since it reminded him of his daughter) but finally did, reluctantly.<ref name=\"Kattabomman\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\n''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' was launched at Annai Illam, Sivaji Ganesan's home.<ref name=\"kungumam\" /> [[Principal photography]] began in October 1957 with a [[Puja (Hinduism)|puja]].<ref name=\"IMN\" /> During filming at [[Bharani Pictures|Bharani Studios]], Madras (now [[Chennai]]) in 1958, [[Adoor Gopalakrishnan]] (who watched the shoot one afternoon) remembered the actors rushing outside after every take because of the intense heat on set: \"The speed of the film was so low those days that one needed many, many lights for correct exposure.\"{{sfn|Bhaskaran|2010|p=47}} Filming also took place prominently in [[Jaipur]]. With the aid of Janakaraja (who was in charge of the cavalry division), the production unit hired [[Extra (acting)|junior artistes]] to play cavalry soldiers in the battle scenes. This was where the final filming schedule took place, and principal photography ended in the same year, around late November to early December.{{Sfn|Ganesan|Narayana Swamy|2007|p=121}}<ref>{{Cite book |title=Eternal Romantic: My Father Gemini Ganesan |last=Ganesh |first=Narayani |publisher=Lustre Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-81-7436-578-1 |page=106 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' was the first Tamil film released in [[Technicolor]];<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article294362.ece |title=One hundred years of superstardom |last=Narayanan |first=Sharadha |date=24 October 2010 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=24 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324054201/http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article294362.ece |archive-date=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/regional/stories-of-indian-freedom-struggle-told-through-tamil-films_160111.html |title=Stories of Indian freedom struggle told through Tamil films |date=15 August 2014 |access-date=24 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324055510/http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/regional/stories-of-indian-freedom-struggle-told-through-tamil-films_160111.html |archive-date=24 March 2015 |agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service]] |website=[[Zee News]]}}</ref> it was shot in [[Gevacolor]] and then converted into Technicolor in London.<ref name=\"BFTP\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/a-100-goes-unsung/article2853657.ece |title=A 100 goes unsung |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=2 February 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220143805/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/a-100-goes-unsung/article2853657.ece |archive-date=20 February 2015}}</ref> Panthulu adopted the American director [[Cecil B. DeMille]]'s practise of introducing the film on-camera.{{Sfnm|1a1=Guy|1y=1997|1p=282|2a1=Rajadhyaksha|2a2=Willemen|2y=1998|2p=361}} The film's final length was {{Convert|18086|feet|metres}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/VeerapandiyaKattabommanCBFC |title=Veera Pandiya Kattabomman (Celluloid) |date=11 April 1959 |publisher=[[Central Board of Film Certification]] |access-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Veerapandiya Kattabomman\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = [[G. Ramanathan]]\n| cover        = \n| border       = yes\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| released     = 1959<ref name=\"iTunes\" />\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = 34:36\n| language     = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\nThe soundtrack album was composed by [[G. Ramanathan]], with lyrics by [[Ku. Ma. Balasubramaniam]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0001250 |title=Veerapandia Kattabomman (1959) |website=[[Raaga.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XGFpc80z?url=http://play.raaga.com/tamil/album/veerapandia-kattabomman-T0001250 |archive-date=24 March 2015 |access-date=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"iTunes\" /> Its songs range from \"[[Tamil folk culture|folksy]] to light to [[Carnatic music|classical]]\".<ref name=\"BR\" /> The soundtrack was a career breakthrough for struggling playback singer [[P. B. Sreenivas]], who was recruited by Ramanathan to sing the duet \"Inbam Pongum Vennila\", with [[P. Susheela]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/veteran-singer-pbs-passes-away/article4617069.ece |title=Veteran singer PBS passes away |last=Kolappan |first=B. |date=14 April 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=29 July 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324060218/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/veteran-singer-pbs-passes-away/article4617069.ece |archive-date=24 March 2015}}</ref> Some of the songs are set in [[Carnatic raga]]s; \"Pogaathe Pogaathe\" is set in [[Kharaharapriya#Janya r\u0101gams|Mukhari]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/notes-of-peace/article4272618.ece |title=Notes of peace |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |date=4 January 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324061050/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/notes-of-peace/article4272618.ece |archive-date=24 March 2015 |author-link=Charulatha Mani}}</ref> \"Manam Kanintharul\" in Kurinji, and \"Singara Kanne\" in Brindavanasaranga.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mambalamtimes.in/admin/pdf/1432379843.MBT%2052%20Pages.pdf |title=Tamil Cinema 75&nbsp;\u2013 A Look Back |last=Guy |first=Randor |date=May 2015 |work=Mambalam Times |access-date=11 May 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511080636/http://mambalamtimes.in/admin/pdf/1432379843.MBT%2052%20Pages.pdf |archive-date=11 May 2016 |page=2 |author-link=Randor Guy}}</ref> Stage actor K. B. Chellamuthu was the songs' violinist.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/faithful-to-his-mentors-memories/article3183749.ece |title=Faithful to his mentor's memories |last=Prabu |first=M. J. |date=26 February 2006 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=25 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325141410/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/faithful-to-his-mentors-memories/article3183749.ece |archive-date=25 March 2015}}</ref> A remix of \"Inbam Pongum Vennila\" was recorded by [[Hiphop Tamizha]] for the 2015 film, ''[[Aambala]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/and-the-film-ends-on-a-happy-note/article6695398.ece |title=And the film ends on a happy note |date=16 December 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324055350/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/and-the-film-ends-on-a-happy-note/article6695398.ece |archive-date=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/aambala-audio-review-news-tamil-om3qFwaeehdib.html |title=Aambala -Audio review |date=29 December 2014 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402085737/http://www.sify.com/movies/aambala-audio-review-news-tamil-om3qFwaeehdib.html |archive-date=2 April 2015 |access-date=1 April 2015}}</ref><!-- try sorting according to this tracklist: https://www.discogs.com/G-Ramanathan-Veerapandiya-Kattabomman/release/9351535 or this: https://www.discogs.com/G-Ramanathan-Veerapandiya-Kattabomman/release/9358116 -->\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Singer(s)\n| all_lyrics = [[Ku. Ma. Balasubramaniam]]\n| total_length    = 34:36<ref name=\"iTunes\" />\n| title1 = Inbam Pongum Vennila\n| extra1 = [[P. B. Sreenivas]], [[P. Susheela]]\n| length1 = 4:42\n| title2 = Maattuvandi Pootikittu\n| extra2 = [[T. M. Soundararajan]], [[T. V. Rathinam]]\n| length2 = 2:53\n| title3 = Seermevum\n| extra3 = Chorus\n| length3 = 0:42\n| title4 = Anjatha Singam\n| extra4 = P. Susheela\n| length4 = 3:26\n| title5 = Aathukkulle\n| extra5 = [[Thiruchi Loganathan]], [[Jamuna Rani]], V. T. Rajagopalan, A. G. Rathnamala\n| length5 = 3:14\n| title6 = Singara Kanne\n| extra6 = [[S. Varalakshmi]]\n| length6 = 3:10\n| title7 = Karantha Palaiyum\n| extra7 = T. M. Soundararajan\n| length7 = 2:45\n| title8 = Takku Takku\n| extra8 = P. Susheela, S. Varalakshmi, [[A. P. Komala]]\n| length8 = 3:23\n| title9 = Manam Kanintharul (Vetrivadivelane)\n| extra9 = V. N. Sundharam, S. Varalakshmi\n| length9 = 3:21\n| title10 = Jakkamma\n| extra10 = [[Sirkazhi Govindarajan]]\n| length10 = 3:16\n| title11 =Veerathin Chinname\n| extra11 = Sirkazhi Govindarajan\n| length11 = 1:04\n| title12 = Pogaathe Pogaathe\n| extra12 = [[A. G. Rathnamala]]\n| length12 = 2:40\n}}\n\n== Release and reception ==\n''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' premiered in London on 10 May 1959,<ref name=\"BFTP\" /> and was released in Tamil Nadu six days later.<ref name=\"mohanmuses\" /><ref name=\"kungumam\" /> The film received positive reviews when it was released.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p=283}} ''Ananda Vikatan'', in its 24 May 1959 review, praised Sivaji Ganesan's performance and said that the film would make a Tamil proud.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=24 May 1959 |title=\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bae\u0bcd: \u0bb5\u0bc0\u0bb0\u0baa\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf \u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0baa\u0bca\u0bae\u0bcd\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bcd |trans-title=Movie Review: Veerapandiya Kattabomman |magazine=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=Tamil}}</ref> Distributed by Padmini Pictures,{{Sfn|Dechamma C. C.|Prakash|2010|p=113}} the film was a commercial success, running for over 25 weeks in theatres, becoming a [[silver jubilee]] film.{{Sfnm|1a1=Ganesan|1a2=Narayana Swamy|1y=2007|1p=241|2a1=Dechamma C. C.|2a2=Prakash|2y=2010|2p=152}}{{efn|A Silver Jubilee film is one that completes a theatrical run of 25 weeks or 175 days.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/disappointing-year-for-telugu-tinseltown/article6734032.ece |title=Disappointing year for Telugu tinseltown |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=Suresh |date=29 December 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=10 January 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110073844/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/disappointing-year-for-telugu-tinseltown/article6734032.ece |archive-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>}} It was dubbed and released in Telugu as ''Veerapandiya Kattabrahmanna'' in 1959, and in Hindi as ''Amar Shaheed'' a year later.{{Sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=361}}<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6ONl7Z5Jvdw |title=Veerapandya Kattabrahmana |date=1959 |last=[[B. R. Panthulu|Panthulu, B. R.]] (director) |type=motion picture |language=Telugu |publisher=Padmini Pictures |place=India}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\nAt the Afro-Asian Film Festival held held from 29 February to 11 March 1960 at Cairo, Ganesan won the Best Actor award;<ref name=\"Cairo\" /> this made him the first Indian actor to receive an international award,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Sivaji-Ganesans-birth-anniversary/articleshow/23338524.cms? |title=Sivaji Ganesan's birth anniversary |date=1 October 2013 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=26 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XJoRZkLs?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Sivaji-Ganesans-birth-anniversary/articleshow/23338524.cms |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref> and he received his award from [[President of Egypt|Egyptian president]] [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Khajane |first=Muralidhara |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/a-born-showman/article528992.ece |title=A born showman |date=23 July 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=15 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130704092234/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/a-born-showman/article528992.ece |archive-date=4 July 2013}}</ref> When Ganesan returned to Madras, [[South Indian Film Chamber of Commerce|South Indian Actors Guild]] president [[M. G. Ramachandran]] organised a large welcome reception for him.{{Sfn|Veeravalli|2013|p=26}} Ganesan wrote in his autobiography that at the festival, \"I was called on stage and I went up a diminutive, five-foot nothing, looking boyish with my build, whereas they had expected me to be a colossus, on seeing [Veerapandiya] Kattabomman, at least seven or eight feet tall! Irrespective of this they gave me a standing ovation for five minutes.\"{{Sfn|Ganesan|Narayana Swamy|2007|p=129}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Event\n!Category\n!Awardee\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n|[[7th National Film Awards]]\n|[[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Tamil]]\n|B. R. Panthulu\n|<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/7th_nff.pdf |title=7th National Film Awards |publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]] |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326125140/http://dff.nic.in/2011/7th_nff.pdf |archive-date=26 March 2015 |access-date=4 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Afro-Asian Film Festival<br />(11 March 1960)\n|Best Actor\n|Sivaji Ganesan\n|<ref name=\"Cairo\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-miscellaneous/dated-march-17-2010-afroasian-film-festival/article729841.ece |title=dated March 17, 2010: Afro-Asian film festival |date=17 March 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326125636/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-miscellaneous/dated-march-17-2010-afroasian-film-festival/article729841.ece |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|Best Music Director\n|G. Ramanathan\n|{{Sfn|Ganesan|Narayana Swamy|2007|p=129}}\n|-\n|Best Foreign Film\n|B. R. Panthulu\n|<ref>{{Cite news |last=Joseph |first=Praveen |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/kids/a-valiant-warriors-birthplace/article2768236.ece |title=A valiant warrior's birthplace |date=2 January 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326125610/http://www.thehindu.com/features/kids/a-valiant-warriors-birthplace/article2768236.ece |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Historical inaccuracies ==\n''Veerapandiya Kattabomman''{{'s}} historical inaccuracies have been criticised.<ref name=\"BFTP\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Madurai/mkus-film-institute-may-have-a-dream-run/article3344864.ece |title=MKU's film institute may have a dream run |last=Karthikeyan |first=D. |date=23 April 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326132301/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Madurai/mkus-film-institute-may-have-a-dream-run/article3344864.ece |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref> Guy reported in 2015 that a Tamil weekly said, \"[...] a new face called Kattabomman acted brilliantly as Sivaji Ganesan!\"{{efn|Guy refused to reveal the name of the weekly.<ref name=\"BFTP\" />}} According to poet [[Kannadasan]], Kattabomman was not a freedom fighter but a Telugu thief; the [[Maruthu Pandiyar]]s were the real freedom fighters, and he wrote a script about them which was adapted into ''Sivagangai Seemai''.{{Sfn|Dechamma C. C.|Prakash|2010|p=152}} Kannadasan's assertion was supported by writer [[Tamilvanan]], who criticised Kattabomman's glorification.{{Sfn|Dechamma C. C.|Prakash|2010|p=152}} In the 1990s, when politician [[Vaiko]] asked Ganesan if he or the writer had researched Kattabomman, with respect to his walking style, Ganesan admitted that they did not, saying, \"In my mind, that's how I imagined the character. That was the walk of the hero.\"<ref name=\"60 years\" />\n\nIn ''Starlight, Starbright: The Early Tamil Cinema'' Guy noted that according to [[East India Company]] records, Kattabomman was of Telugu ancestry and a strong, silent man (without the film's dash and daring). According to Guy, Ganesan portrayed Kattabomman as a \"larger-than-life-character, haranguing audiences in a high-flown Tamil replete with literary flourishes\"; the real Kattabomman was not fluent in Tamil.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p=282}} Ashish Rajadhyaksha and Paul Willemen's ''Encyclopedia of Indian Cinema'' says, \"A love interest has been added as well\", implying that the character of Vellaiyammal was fictional.{{Sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=361}} Film historian S. Krishnaswamy, writing for ''[[The Hindu]]'' in 2001, noted that the film was \"historically far from accurate\" and \"more like a costume drama or a mythological\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/2001/07/27/stories/09270221.htm |title=The legend lives on... |last=Krishnaswamy |first=S. |date=27 July 2001 |work=The Hindu |access-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406121325/http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/2001/07/27/stories/09270221.htm |archive-date=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2010 book, ''Cinemas of South India: Culture, Resistance, Ideology'', Elavarthi Sathya Prakash says about Kattabomman's Telugu identity: \"While National historiography tries to elevate him, some versions of Tamil history seem to downgrade him\".{{Sfn|Dechamma C. C.|Prakash|2010|p=153}} [[S. Theodore Baskaran]] said the following year, \"Tamil films have scant regard for history. Almost always, they confuse between history and folklore ... Kattabomman was not even a king. His arsenal had just about three to four guns.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/7-aum-arivu-row-debate-rages-over-bodhi-dharma%E2%80%99s-identity-006 |title=7 Aum Arivu row: Debate rages over Bodhi Dharma's identity |last=Muralidharan |first=Kavitha |date=9 November 2011 |work=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |access-date=29 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109212945/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/7-aum-arivu-row-debate-rages-over-bodhi-dharma%E2%80%99s-identity-006 |archive-date=9 November 2011}}</ref> [[University of Madras]] department head Ramu Manivannan told ''The Times of India'' in 2014, \"The popular images of [historical] characters have been constructed from oral descriptions and accounts. In some cases, the popular image overtakes the historical one as in the case of Sivaji Ganesan's portrayal of Kattabomman on the screen.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Did-Thiruvalluvar-really-have-pointy-ribs/articleshow/44831906.cms |title=Did Thiruvalluvar really have pointy ribs? |last=Valsan |first=Binoy |date=16 October 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XZzAQUGs?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Did-Thiruvalluvar-really-have-pointy-ribs/articleshow/44831906.cms |archive-date=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Kattabomman1959.jpg|thumb|upright=.9|alt=Slightly-blurry screenshot from the film|The scene where Kattabomman and Jackson confront each other attained popularity.]]\n''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' achieved [[cult film|cult status]] in Tamil cinema.<ref name=\"BFTP\" /> It was a landmark film in Ganesan's career, and Tamil people identified Kattabomman with him.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/costume-drama/748424/ |title=Costume Drama |last=Ravindran |first=Shruti |date=12 February 2011 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |access-date=9 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409122334/http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/costume-drama/748424/ |archive-date=9 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://m.rediff.com/movies/2001/jul/23siv1.htm |title='We felt we were in the presence of a diety! &#91;sic&#93;' |date=23 July 2001 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409122709/http://m.rediff.com/movies/2001/jul/23siv1.htm |archive-date=9 April 2015 |access-date=9 April 2015}}</ref> N. Sathiya Moorthy wrote for [[Rediff.com]] in 2001, \"[Ganesan's] portrayal of Lord Shiva in [''[[Thiruvilaiyadal]]''] and of freedom-fighters ''Veerapandia Kattabomman'' and ''Kappalottia Thamizhan'' V O Chidambaram have become symbolic of the very characters in the average Tamil mind across the world.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2001/jul/21siv1.htm |title=Sivaji: Actor who revolutionised Tamil cinema |last=Moorthy |first=N Sathiya |date=22 July 2001 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010724222611/http://rediff.com/news/2001/jul/21siv1.htm |archive-date=24 July 2001 |access-date=21 July 2016}}</ref> The film was a trendsetter in Tamil cinema, and a benchmark of dialogue delivery.<ref name=\"roar\" /> Its success encouraged many in Tamil cinema to make films based on freedom fighters and historical figures, notably ''[[Kappalottiya Thamizhan]]'' (1961) and ''[[Bharathi (2000 film)|Bharathi]]'' (2000).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1722/17220890.htm |title=Portrait of a poet |last=Viswanathan |first=S. |date=November 2000 |website=[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110083827/http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1722/17220890.htm |archive-date=10 January 2017 |access-date=10 January 2017}}</ref> The film's ''jallikattu'' scene attained popularity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/cat-and-mouse-over-the-bull-game/298409 |title=Cat-And-Mouse Over The Bull Game |last=Gopalan |first=T. N. |date=6 February 2017 |website=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130073644/http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/cat-and-mouse-over-the-bull-game/298409 |archive-date=30 January 2017 |access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://swarajyamag.com/culture/the-lament-of-tamil-nadu-what-is-pongal-without-jallikattu |title=The Lament of Tamil Nadu: What Is Pongal Without Jallikattu? |date=13 January 2017 |website=[[Swarajya (magazine)|Swarajya]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130073641/https://swarajyamag.com/culture/the-lament-of-tamil-nadu-what-is-pongal-without-jallikattu |archive-date=30 January 2017 |access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref> The term \"Ettappan\" later entered Tamil lexicon as a slang word meaning a traitor, because of the scene where Kattabomman accuses the character of treachery.<ref name=\"60 years\" />\n\nIn 1970, eleven years after ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman''{{'s}} release, Ganesan erected a statue of Kattabomman in Kayatharu (where the rebel was hanged).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/heir-wants-kattabommans-statue-in-chennai/article6205380.ece |title=Heir wants Kattabomman's statue in Chennai |last=Praveen Paul Joseph |first=J. |date=13 July 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406140841/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/heir-wants-kattabommans-statue-in-chennai/article6205380.ece |archive-date=6 April 2015}}</ref> During a February 2009 visit to Sri Lanka, [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] leader [[L. K. Advani]] said: \"I have seen the Tamil movie of [''Veerapandiya Kattabomman''], acted by [Sivaji] Ganesan, many times. It is fresh in my memory.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2009/feb/13sld2-advani-comes-out-in-support-of-lankan-tamils.htm |title=Advani supports Lankan Tamils |date=13 February 2009 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XGkEIcxq?url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2009/feb/13sld2-advani-comes-out-in-support-of-lankan-tamils.htm |archive-date=24 March 2015 |access-date=29 July 2013}}</ref> A [[Cover (philately)|postal cover]], designed by film historian and actor [[Mohan Raman]], was released on 16 May 2009 by the Sivaji\u2013Prabhu Charities trust and the Indo-Russian Cultural and Friendship Society to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the film's release.<ref name=\"mohanmuses\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indianstampghar.com/2009/06/special-cover-veerapandiya-kattabomman-film/ |title=Special Cover&nbsp;\u2013 Veerapandiya Kattabomman Film |date=5 June 2009 |website=Indianstampghar.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XKs5oj6r?url=http://www.indianstampghar.com/2009/06/special-cover-veerapandiya-kattabomman-film/ |archive-date=27 March 2015 |access-date=27 March 2015}}</ref> Politician [[Venkaiah Naidu]] said in 2016 that he became a fan of Sivaji Ganesan after watching his performance in the film.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2016/oct/02/sivaji-lives-with-us-through-his-movies-says-venkaiah-1518784.html |title=Sivaji lives with us through his movies, says Venkaiah |date=2 October 2016 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=4 February 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204054728/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2016/oct/02/sivaji-lives-with-us-through-his-movies-says-venkaiah-1518784.html |archive-date=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nA. V. Ashok wrote for ''The Hindu'', \"It is no exaggeration to say that Sivaji's heroic outpouring as ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' is an integral part of the Tamil cultural psyche.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/07/19/stories/2002071900990600.htm |title=Incredible charisma on screen |last=Ashok |first=A. V. |date=19 July 2002 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326134335/http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/07/19/stories/2002071900990600.htm |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref> According to the actor [[Sivakumar]], \"You can't reproduce movies like ''Parasakthi'', ''[[Pasamalar]]'', ''[[Devadasu (1953 film)|Devadas]]'', ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' or ''[[Ratha Kanneer]]'' [...] By remaking such films, you are lowering yourself, while it enhances the original artists\u2019 image.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/sivakumar-not-for-old-wine-in-new-bottle/article1170631.ece |title=Sivakumar not for old wine in new bottle |last=Anand |first=N. |date=3 January 2008 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326134402/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/sivakumar-not-for-old-wine-in-new-bottle/article1170631.ece |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref> An elephant presented by Ganesan to the [[Punnainallur Mariamman]] temple in 1960 was named \"Vellaiyammal\" (after Padmini's character), and was later donated to the [[Brihadisvara Temple, Thanjavur]] in 1980.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/trumpet-of-vellaiyammal-at-big-temple-in-thanjavur-falls-silent/article5130903.ece |title=Trumpet of Vellaiyammal at Big Temple in Thanjavur falls silent |last=Srinivasan |first=G. |date=15 September 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326134847/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/trumpet-of-vellaiyammal-at-big-temple-in-thanjavur-falls-silent/article5130903.ece |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref> According to [[Sri Lankan Canadians|Sri Lankan Canadian]] journalist [[D. B. S. Jeyaraj]], ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' was the first Tamil film that had a great impact on him; the film's success \"was the powerful delivery of fiery dialogue by the film hero Kattabomman played by Sivaji.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ft.lk/article/328270/Sivaji-Ganesan---Tamil-cinema-s-versatile-actor-par-excellence |title=Sivaji Ganesan: Tamil cinema\u2019s versatile actor par excellence |last=Jeyaraj |first=D. B. S. |date=26 July 2014 |work=[[Daily FT]] |access-date=11 July 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110082859/http://www.ft.lk/article/328270/Sivaji-Ganesan---Tamil-cinema-s-versatile-actor-par-excellence |archive-date=10 January 2017 |author-link=D. B. S. Jeyaraj}}</ref>\n\nGanesan's line \"''Vari, vatti, kisthi&nbsp;... Yaarai ketkirai vari ... Etharkku ketkirai vari. Vaanam polikirathu, bhumi vilaigirathu, unakken katta vendum vari ... ''\" (roughly translated \"Tribute, tax, loan, interest. The rains pour from the sky, the land blossoms, why should I offer you money?\"),{{Sfn|Ganesan|Narayana Swamy|2007|p=169}} from a scene with C. R. Parthiban, was ranked eighth on ''[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]]''{{'}}s 20 October 2008 list of 13 Cheesiest, Chalkiest Lines in Indian Cinema.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/13-Cheesiest-Chalkiest-Lines-In-Indian-Cinema/238709 |title=13 cheesiest, chalkiest lines in Indian cinema |date=20 October 2008 |website=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326142610/http://www.outlookindia.com/article/13-Cheesiest-Chalkiest-Lines-In-Indian-Cinema/238709 |archive-date=26 March 2015 |access-date=26 March 2015}}</ref> In April 2012, Rediff.com included the film on its A to Z of Tamil Cinema list.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-the-a-to-z-of-tamil-cinema/20120418.htm?print=true |title=Special: The A to Z of Tamil Cinema |last=Srinivasan |first=Pavithra |date=18 April 2012 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411111521/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-the-a-to-z-of-tamil-cinema/20120418.htm?print=true |archive-date=11 April 2015 |access-date=11 April 2015}}</ref> In a January 2015 interview with ''The Times of India'', playwright [[Y. G. Mahendran]] said: \"Most character artists today lack variety [...] Show me one actor in India currently who can do a Kattabomman, a [[V. O. Chidambaram Pillai|VOC]], a ''[[Vietnam Veedu]]'', a ''[[Galatta Kalyanam]]'' and a ''[[Thiruvilaiyadal|Thiruvilayadal]]''.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Oscar-worthy-performance-by-Sivaji-Y-Gee-Mahendra/articleshow/45883224.cms |title=Oscar-worthy performance by Sivaji: Y Gee Mahendra |date=14 January 2015 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XVOxkz6M?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Oscar-worthy-performance-by-Sivaji-Y-Gee-Mahendra/articleshow/45883224.cms |archive-date=3 April 2015}}</ref> Actor [[Rana Daggubati]], in an interview with Sangeetha Devi Dundoo of ''The Hindu'', said that Ganesan's performances as Kattabomman and [[Karna]] (in the 1964 film ''[[Karnan (film)|Karnan]]'') influenced his role in ''[[Baahubali: The Beginning|Baahubali]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/rana-daggubati-on-a-warrior-mode/article7057707.ece |title=On a warrior mode |last=Dundoo |first=Sangeetha Devi |date=2 April 2015 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406054346/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/rana-daggubati-on-a-warrior-mode/article7057707.ece |archive-date=6 April 2015}}</ref> The scene between Ganesan and Parthiban was featured in the 2016 film, ''[[Jackson Durai]]'',<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/Jackson-Durai-A-well-crafted-misfire/article14499263.ece |title=Jackson Durai: A well-crafted misfire |last=Rangan |first=Baradwaj |date=1 July 2016 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=10 January 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110135343/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/Jackson-Durai-A-well-crafted-misfire/article14499263.ece |archive-date=10 January 2017 |author-link=Baradwaj Rangan}}</ref> which was named after Parthiban's character.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://baradwajrangan.wordpress.com/2016/12/23/balle-vellaiya-thevaa-barely-any-laughs-for-a-comedy/ |title=\"Balle Vellaiya Thevaa\"... Barely any laughs for a \"comedy\" |last=Rangan |first=Baradwaj |date=23 December 2016 |publisher=Baradwajrangan.wordpress.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110135658/https://baradwajrangan.wordpress.com/2016/12/23/balle-vellaiya-thevaa-barely-any-laughs-for-a-comedy/ |archive-date=10 January 2017 |access-date=10 January 2017}}</ref> [[M. Sasikumar]]'s ''[[Balle Vellaiyathevaa]]'', also released that year, was named after a line spoken by Ganesan's character.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://newstodaynet.com/entertainment/i-never-glorify-caste-my-films-sasikumar |title=I never glorify caste in my films: Sasikumar |last=Kumar |first=M Bharat |date=16 December 2016 |work=[[The News Today (India)|The News Today]] |access-date=10 January 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110151542/http://newstodaynet.com/entertainment/i-never-glorify-caste-my-films-sasikumar |archive-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Re-releases ==\nThe film was re-released in 1984 during M. G. Ramachandran's tenure as [[List of chief ministers of Tamil Nadu|Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu]]. Granted [[tax exemption]] by the state government, it was again commercially successful and ran for 30 weeks in theatres.<ref name=\"Pyramids TNIE\" /> In 2012, after the commercial success of ''Karnan''{{'s}} digital re-release, [[Raj Television Network]] announced that they would re-release ''Veerapandiya Kattabomman'' in [[3D film|3D]] in early 2013;<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Kattabomman-in-3D/articleshow/12492246.cms |title=Kattabomman in 3D! |last=Suganth |first=M. |date=2 April 2012 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=25 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XJXtkP02?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Kattabomman-in-3D/articleshow/12492246.cms |archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref> however, that did not happen.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/tamil-classic-karnan-is-still-ruling-the-kollywood-box-office/378092-71-180.html |title=Tamil classic 'Karnan' is still ruling the Kollywood box office |date=11 March 2013 |website=[[CNN-News18]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326123105/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/tamil-classic-karnan-is-still-ruling-the-kollywood-box-office/378092-71-180.html |archive-date=26 March 2015 |access-date=20 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Raj Television Network announced that they would release a digital [[5.1 surround sound]] version of the film in collaboration with Sai Ganesh Films the following month;<ref name=\"Thrill\" /> it was released on 21 August of that year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/friday-fury-august-21-news-tamil-pivknhdgihcgi.html |title=Friday Fury- August 21 |date=21 August 2015 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511052753/http://www.sify.com/movies/friday-fury-august-21-news-tamil-pivknhdgihcgi.html |archive-date=11 May 2016 |access-date=10 May 2016}}</ref> Murali B. V., coordinator of Sai Ganesh Films (which helped restore and digitise the film's original prints), told ''[[The New Indian Express]]'' that it took nine months to clean and restore the original [[35 mm movie film|35 mm film]] (with [[monaural]] sound) for digitisation.<ref name=\"Pyramids TNIE\" /><ref name=\"Thrill\" /> A reviewer for ''[[The Times of India]]'' criticised the digitised version, noting that the colour \"seemed to have been leached [from] the frames\" and the sound system was \"a bit contemporary.\" Despite its technical issues, however, \"the film still retains its dramatic force\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Veerapandiya-Kattabomman/movie-review/48609800.cms |title=Veerapandiya Kattabomman Movie Review |date=22 August 2015 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=22 August 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6axvaW1so?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Veerapandiya-Kattabomman/movie-review/48609800.cms |archive-date=22 August 2015}}</ref> Likewise, film critic [[Baradwaj Rangan]] wrote, \"The picture quality&nbsp;\u2013 the colours, mainly&nbsp;\u2013 is a bit inconsistent. But this may be due to problems with the negative, and it doesn't affect the three-hour film at all&nbsp;\u2013 save for the war portions where we wait for the inevitable, it all just zips by.\"<ref name=\"BR\" /> The digitised version earned {{INR}}553,000 in its opening weekend from 39 shows in Chennai,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kick-2-first-weekend-box-office-collection-ravi-teja-starrer-loses-simbus-vaalu-aryas-643964 |title='Kick 2' First Weekend Box Office Collection: Ravi Teja Starrer Loses to Simbu's 'Vaalu', Arya's 'VSOP' in Chennai |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=24 August 2015 |work=[[International Business Times]] |access-date=24 August 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824214916/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kick-2-first-weekend-box-office-collection-ravi-teja-starrer-loses-simbus-vaalu-aryas-643964 |archive-date=24 August 2015}}</ref> and was a commercial success.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/unattainable-heights-nadigar-thilagam-chevalier-sivaji-ganesan-49646 |title=The unattainable heights of Nadigar Thilagam Chevalier Sivaji Ganesan |last=Aravind |first=C. V. |date=10 September 2016 |work=[[The News Minute]] |access-date=10 January 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110090018/http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/unattainable-heights-nadigar-thilagam-chevalier-sivaji-ganesan-49646 |archive-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Credits\">{{Cite AV media |title=Veerapandiya Kattabomman |last=Panthulu |first=B. R. |type=motion picture |language=Tamil |publisher=Padmini Pictures |year=1959 |author-link=B. R. Panthulu |place=India |time=2:00 to 2:24 |time-caption=From}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kattabomman\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-power-of-the-pen/article4594630.ece |title=The power of the pen |last=Raman |first=Mohan V. |date=8 April 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=20 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220142438/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-power-of-the-pen/article4594630.ece |archive-date=20 February 2015 |author-link=Mohan Raman}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"roar\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/multilingual-musical-tribute-to-msv/article7484458.ece |title=Kattabomman to roa