{"title_page": "Eucalyptus clelandiorum", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Cleland's blackbutt\n|image = Eucalyptus clelandiorum.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Eucalyptus clelandiorum'' growing north of [[Kalgoorlie]]\n|status_system = \n|status =\n|genus = Eucalyptus\n|species = clelandiorum\n|authority = ([[Joseph Maiden|Maiden]]) Maiden<ref name=APC>{{cite web|title=''Eucalyptus clelandiorum''|url= https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/112799|publisher=Australian Plant Census|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n|synonyms_ref =<ref name=\"APC\" />\n|synonyms =\n* ''Eucalyptus clelandi'' <small>Maiden [[Orthographical variant|orth. var.]]</small>\n* ''Eucalyptus clelandii'' <small>H.Eichler orth. var.</small>\n* ''Eucalyptus goniantha'' var. ''clelandi'' <small>Maiden orth. var.</small>\n* ''Eucalyptus goniantha'' var. ''clelandiorum'' <small>Maiden</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Eucalyptus clelandiorum''''', commonly known as '''Cleland's blackbutt'''<ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Eucalyptus clelandiorum''|id=48436}}</ref> is a species of [[Mallet (habit)|mallet]] that is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[South West (Western Australia)|South West]] region of [[Western Australia]]. It has hard, black, crumbly bark on the lower half of its trunk, smooth bark above, narrow lance-shaped adult leaves, flower buds arranged in groups of seven, nine or eleven, white flowers and cup-shaped fruit.[[File:Eucalyptus clelandiorum buds.jpg|thumb|flower buds]][[File:Eucalyptus clelandiorum fruit.jpg|thumb|fruit]]\n\n==Description==\n''Eucalyptus clelandiorum'' is a mallet that typically grows to a height of {{cvt|10|m}} and does not form a [[lignotuber]]. It has hard, black, crumbly bark on about the lower half of the trunk, and smooth pale grey to pinkish bark above. The leaves on young plants and on [[coppice]] regrowth are [[wikt:glaucous#Adjective|glaucous]], broadly lance-shaped to egg-shaped, up to {{cvt|80|mm}} long and {{cvt|35|mm}} wide. The adult leaves are the same dull greyish green or glaucous on both sides, narrow lance-shaped, {{cvt|80-155|mm}} long and {{cvt|9-25|mm}} wide.The flower buds are arranged in groups of seven, nine or eleven in leaf [[wikt:axil|axil]]s on a [[Peduncle (botany)|peduncle]] {{cvt|6-15|mm}} long, the individual buds on a [[Pedicel (botany)|pedicel]] {{cvt|1-5|mm}} long. Mature buds are oval, {{cvt|7-12|mm}} long and {{cvt|4-7|mm}} wide and glaucous with a beaked [[Operculum (botany)|operculum]] {{cvt|4-6|mm}} long. Flowering mainly occurs from August to November and the flowers are white. The fruit is a woody cup-shaped [[Capsule (botany)|capsule]] {{cvt|5-9|mm}} long and {{cvt|5-8|mm}} wide on a pedicel {{cvt|1-6|mm}} long.<ref name=\"FloraBase\" /><ref name=\"CANBR\">{{cite web |title=''Eucalyptus clelandiorum'' |url=http://keyserver.lucidcentral.org:8080/euclid/data/02050e02-0108-490e-8900-0e0601070d00/media/Html/Eucalyptus_clelandii.htm |publisher=Euclid: Centre for Australian National Biodiversity Research |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ABRS\">{{cite web |last1=Chippendale |first1=George M. |title=''Eucalyptus clelandii'' |url=https://profiles.ala.org.au/opus/foa/profile/Eucalyptus%20clelandii |publisher=Australian Biological Resources Study, Department of the Environment and Energy, Canberra |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nCleland's blackbutt was first formally described in 1911 by [[Joseph Maiden]] who gave it the name ''Eucalyptus goniantha'' var. ''clelandiorum'' and published the description in the ''Journal of the Natural History and Science Society of Western Australia''.<ref name=APNI1>{{cite web|title=''Eucalyptus goniantha'' var. ''clelandiorum''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/454666 |publisher=APNI|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Maiden\">{{cite journal |last1=Maiden |first1=Joseph |title=Notes on Western Australian eucalypts, including description of new species |journal=Journal of the Natural History & Science Society of Western Australia |date=1911 |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=176\u2013177 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/216975#page/214/mode/1up |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> In 1912, Maiden raised the variety to species status in his book ''A Critical Revision of the Genus Eucalyptus''.<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Eucalyptus clelandiorum''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/455999 |publisher=APNI|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"revision\">{{cite book |last1=Maiden |first1=Joseph |title=A critical revision of the genus ''Eucalyptus'' (Volume 2) |date=1912 |publisher=N.S.W. Government Printer |location=Sydney |page=189 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/123249#page/303/mode/1up |accessdate=8 March 2019}}</ref> The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] (''clelandiorum'') honours \"Mr. A.F. Cleland, Civil Engineer of Kurrawang\" and his nephew, \"[[John Burton Cleland|Dr. J. Burton Cleland]]\".<ref name=\"Maiden\" />\n\n==Distribution==\n''Eucalyptus clelandiorum'' mostly grows in open woodland from east of [[Cue, Western Australia|Cue]] to near [[Lake Biddy, Western Australia|Lake Biddy]] in the [[Avon Wheatbelt]], [[Coolgardie (biogeographic region)|Coolgardie]], [[Great Victoria Desert]], [[Murchison (biogeographic region)|Murchison]] and [[Yalgoo (biogeographic region)|Yalgoo]] [[IBRA|biogeographic regions]] of Western Australia.<ref name=\"FloraBase\" /><ref name=\"ABRS\" />\n\n==Conservation status==\nThis mallet is classified as \"not threatened\" by the Western Australian Government [[Department of Parks and Wildlife (Western Australia)|Department of Parks and Wildlife]].<ref name=\"FloraBase\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Eucalyptus species|List of ''Eucalyptus'' species]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5405561}}\n\n[[Category:Eucalyptus|clelandiorum]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Mallees (habit)]]\n[[Category:Myrtales of Australia]]\n[[Category:Rosids of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1911]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Joseph Maiden]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|name = Cleland's blackbutt\n|image = Eucalyptus clelandiorum.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Eucalyptus clelandiorum'' growing north of [[Kalgoorlie]]\n|status_system = \n|status =\n|genus = Eucalyptus\n|species = clelandiorum\n|authority = ([[Joseph Maiden|Maiden]]) Maiden<ref name=APC>{{cite web|title=''Eucalyptus clelandiorum''|url= https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/112799|publisher=Australian Plant Census|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n|synonyms_ref =<ref name=\"APC\" />\n|synonyms =\n* ''Eucalyptus clelandi'' <small>Maiden [[Orthographical variant|orth. var.]]</small>\n* ''Eucalyptus clelandii'' <small>H.Eichler orth. var.</small>\n* ''Eucalyptus goniantha'' var. ''clelandi'' <small>Maiden orth. var.</small>\n* ''Eucalyptus goniantha'' var. ''clelandiorum'' <small>Maiden</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Eucalyptus clelandiorum''''', commonly known as '''Cleland's blackbutt'''<ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Eucalyptus clelandiorum''|id=48436}}</ref> is a species of [[Mallet (habit)|mallet]] that is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[South West (Western Australia)|South West]] region of [[Western Australia]]. It has hard, black, crumbly bark on the lower half of its trunk, smooth bark above, narrow lance-shaped adult leaves, flower buds arranged in groups of seven, nine or eleven, white flowers and cup-shaped fruit.[[File:Eucalyptus clelandiorum buds.jpg|thumb|flower buds]][[File:Eucalyptus clelandiorum fruit.jpg|thumb|fruit]]\n\n==Description==\n''Eucalyptus clelandiorum'' is a mallet that typically grows to a height of {{cvt|10|m}} and does not form a [[lignotuber]]. It has hard, black, crumbly bark on about the lower half of the trunk, and smooth pale grey to pinkish bark above. The leaves on young plants and on [[coppice]] regrowth are [[wikt:glaucous#Adjective|glaucous]], broadly lance-shaped to egg-shaped, up to {{cvt|80|mm}} long and {{cvt|35|mm}} wide. The adult leaves are the same dull greyish green or glaucous on both sides, narrow lance-shaped, {{cvt|80-155|mm}} long and {{cvt|9-25|mm}} wide.The flower buds are arranged in groups of seven, nine or eleven in leaf [[wikt:axil|axil]]s on a [[Peduncle (botany)|peduncle]] {{cvt|6-15|mm}} long, the individual buds on a [[Pedicel (botany)|pedicel]] {{cvt|1-5|mm}} long. Mature buds are oval, {{cvt|7-12|mm}} long and {{cvt|4-7|mm}} wide and glaucous with a beaked [[Operculum (botany)|operculum]] {{cvt|4-6|mm}} long. Flowering mainly occurs from August to November and the flowers are white. The fruit is a woody cup-shaped [[Capsule (botany)|capsule]] {{cvt|5-9|mm}} long and {{cvt|5-8|mm}} wide on a pedicel {{cvt|1-6|mm}} long.<ref name=\"FloraBase\" /><ref name=\"CANBR\">{{cite web |title=''Eucalyptus clelandiorum'' |url=http://keyserver.lucidcentral.org:8080/euclid/data/02050e02-0108-490e-8900-0e0601070d00/media/Html/Eucalyptus_clelandii.htm |publisher=Euclid: Centre for Australian National Biodiversity Research |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ABRS\">{{cite web |last1=Chippendale |first1=George M. |title=''Eucalyptus clelandii'' |url=https://profiles.ala.org.au/opus/foa/profile/Eucalyptus%20clelandii |publisher=Australian Biological Resources Study, Department of the Environment and Energy, Canberra |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nCleland's blackbutt was first formally described in 1911 by [[Joseph Maiden]] who gave it the name ''Eucalyptus goniantha'' var. ''clelandiorum'' and published the description in the ''Journal of the Natural History and Science Society of Western Australia''.<ref name=APNI1>{{cite web|title=''Eucalyptus goniantha'' var. ''clelandiorum''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/454666 |publisher=APNI|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Maiden\">{{cite journal |last1=Maiden |first1=Joseph |title=Notes on Western Australian eucalypts, including description of new species |journal=Journal of the Natural History & Science Society of Western Australia |date=1911 |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=176\u2013177 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/216975#page/214/mode/1up |accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> In 1912, Maiden raised the variety to species status in his book ''A Critical Revision of the Genus Eucalyptus''.<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Eucalyptus clelandiorum''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/455999 |publisher=APNI|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"revision\">{{cite book |last1=Maiden |first1=Joseph |title=A critical revision of the genus ''Eucalyptus'' (Volume 2) |date=1912 |publisher=N.S.W. Government Printer |location=Sydney |page=189 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/123249#page/303/mode/1up |accessdate=8 March 2019}}</ref> The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] (''clelandiorum'') honours \"Mr. A.F. Cleland, Civil Engineer of Kurrawang\" and his nephew, \"[[John Burton Cleland|Dr. J. Burton Cleland]]\".<ref name=\"Maiden\" />\n\n==Distribution==\n''Eucalyptus clelandiorum'' mostly grows in open woodland from east of [[Cue, Western Australia|Cue]] to near [[Lake Biddy, Western Australia|Lake Biddy]] in the [[Avon Wheatbelt]], [[Coolgardie (biogeographic region)|Coolgardie]], [[Great Victoria Desert]], [[Murchison (biogeographic region)|Murchison]] and [[Yalgoo (biogeographic region)|Yalgoo]] [[IBRA|biogeographic regions]] of Western Australia.<ref name=\"FloraBase\" /><ref name=\"ABRS\" />\n\n==Conservation status==\nThis mallet is classified as \"not threatened\" by the Western Australian Government [[Department of Parks and Wildlife (Western Australia)|Department of Parks and Wildlife]].<ref name=\"FloraBase\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Eucalyptus species|List of ''Eucalyptus'' species]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5405561}}\n\n[[Category:Eucalyptus|clelandiorum]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Mallees (habit)]]\n[